{"term":"1957","caseName":"National Association for the Advancement of Colored People v. Patterson","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1957/91","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - January 15, 1958","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13364","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Next case is Number 91, National Association for the Advancement of Colored People Corporation versus State of Alabama on the relation of John Patterson, Attorney General.","start":0,"stop":51.272,"duration":51.27},{"text":"Mr. Carter, you may proceed.","start":51.272,"stop":55.466,"duration":4.19}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"If the Court please.","start":55.466,"stop":58.592,"duration":3.13},{"text":"This calls us here from a judgment of the Supreme Court of Alabama, dismissing and denying a petition for writ of certiorari filed by petitioner seeking to review in the Alabama Court an adjudication of contempt and a fine in the sum of $100,000 on the failure of petitioner to submit its membership lists pursuant to an order of the Circuit Court of Montgomery County.","start":58.592,"stop":88.304,"duration":29.71},{"text":"The issues arose in the following manner.","start":88.304,"stop":92.643,"duration":4.34},{"text":"On June 1, 1956, the Attorney General filed the bill of complaint in the Circuit Court of Montgomery County, alleging that petitioner was doing business in Alabama without complying with the Foreign Registration Act of Alabama.","start":92.643,"stop":114.019,"duration":21.38},{"text":"And alleging, in addition, various of illegal acts, the -- the two that they've named was the fact that the allegation was that petitioner had given moneys to two persons to induce them to apply to the University of Alabama to test these policies excluding Negroes on the basis of race.","start":114.019,"stop":135.59,"duration":21.57}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Your State is in New York, the State of the corporation?","start":135.59,"stop":138.164,"duration":2.57}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":138.164,"stop":140.316,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"When you say incorporation, would you mind being a little more specific?","start":140.316,"stop":144.756,"duration":4.44}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"We're incorporated in New York.","start":144.756,"stop":146.619,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Under -- under what?","start":146.619,"stop":147.658,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Under the New York membership (Inaudible) --","start":147.658,"stop":149.171,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that -- that's what I meant.","start":149.171,"stop":150.462,"duration":1.29},{"text":"It's a particular kind of associated body, isn't it?","start":150.462,"stop":153.201,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":153.201,"stop":154.55,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What -- under what law did you say the case is?","start":154.55,"stop":156.641,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"I didn't hear you.","start":156.641,"stop":157.515,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Under what --","start":157.515,"stop":158.054,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"New York Membership.","start":158.054,"stop":159.359,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Membership?","start":159.359,"stop":159.849,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":159.849,"stop":160.36,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":160.36,"stop":161.059,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Membership Corporations Act.","start":161.059,"stop":162.894,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that -- excuse me, makes anybody corporate however, does it not?","start":162.894,"stop":166.417,"duration":3.52}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":166.417,"stop":166.582,"duration":0.16}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"To get his New York citizenship?","start":166.582,"stop":168.09,"duration":1.51}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":168.09,"stop":173.336,"duration":5.25}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"What have you done in Alabama (Voice Overlap) -- what law -- rather, what did they charged you with failing to do it for them.","start":173.336,"stop":181.945,"duration":8.61}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"They charged that we have failed to register as a foreign corporation that we were doing business in Alabama without first complying with this Act which requires foreign corporations to submit their articles in a corporation to the Secretary of State and designate a place of business, but --","start":181.945,"stop":200.435,"duration":18.49}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"The common statute is complying in (Inaudible) every State requires a foreign corporation as a condition (Inaudible) by obtaining a certificate to the procedures provided to deliver the thing.","start":200.435,"stop":215.32,"duration":14.88}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Precisely.","start":215.32,"stop":215.989,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":215.989,"stop":217.427,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The issue here is whether or not they obtained a (Inaudible).","start":217.427,"stop":221.307,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":221.307,"stop":223.119,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":223.119,"stop":225.722,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, in addition to this failure, they charge that we have done other illegal acts.","start":225.722,"stop":234.888,"duration":9.17},{"text":"And as I started to indicate, the acts that they're charge were that we've given money -- alleged that we've given money to two persons to induce them to enroll at the University of Alabama to test this policy that we had furnished counsel for these persons and that we had incited and aided the Montgomery citizens to boycott the bus lines when they were attempting to secure unsegregated (Inaudible).","start":234.888,"stop":264.401,"duration":29.51},{"text":"On the basis of these allegations alone and without a hearing and with nothing further, we were without notice, enjoined from operation.","start":264.401,"stop":276.186,"duration":11.78},{"text":"The -- the State asked that we'd be enjoined from all organizational activities.","start":276.186,"stop":281.306,"duration":5.12},{"text":"We were so enjoined ex parte and in addition although this was not requested by the State, the Court enjoined us from taking any steps to comply with the law of requiring foreign corporations to domesticate.","start":281.306,"stop":297.74,"duration":16.43},{"text":"Now, we then filed on July 2nd a motion to vacate to dissolve the -- the injunction of temporary decree, which is the procedure that one follows an Alabama Law.","start":297.74,"stop":316.129,"duration":18.39},{"text":"On July 5th, the State came with a motion requiring us to produce pretrial production of various doctrines, including a list of our members and various other items.","start":316.129,"stop":330.146,"duration":14.02},{"text":"This motion was heard on July 9 and on July 9 towards July 11, the Court ordered us to produce these various items including a list of our members and we've cited the -- the specific things that the Court asked that are cited on pages 6, 7, and 8 of our petition filed here.","start":330.146,"stop":352.06,"duration":21.91},{"text":"The Court asked that these or these items be produced on July 16, but it subsequently extended the time for us to produce until July 25th and then simultaneously continued the hearing on the motion to dissolve to July 25th.","start":352.06,"stop":372.009,"duration":19.95},{"text":"We then filed an answer on July 23rd in which we admitted that we had -- that we were -- had charted branches in the State that we had been in Alabama since 1918, that we had not registered under the -- under the Act because it was our good faith belief that we were not required to do so that we had not furnished any moneys to anybody to enroll in the University of Alabama although we did admit that we've furnished legal counsel and aide to Ms. Lucy to prosecute our suit, but we have not participated in the Montgomery situation, but that we had given financial assistance and legal aide to the persons who were charged with -- with violations of the State law from refusing to ride the buses unsegregated.","start":372.009,"stop":430.694,"duration":58.69},{"text":"We are -- in our answer, we said that although we do not feel that we are obliged to abide this law, we attached the -- the requisite form and asked the Court to resend its order and vacate its order, barring us from registry so that we could comply with the law.","start":430.694,"stop":452.237,"duration":21.54},{"text":"In other words, we indicate that we're willing to wait whatever contentions we had on that ground.","start":452.237,"stop":458.769,"duration":6.53},{"text":"With this answer, we filed the motion to vacate the interlocutory order of the Court requiring us to produce on constitutional ground and on the ground that the issue was no longer -- the issue of the -- getting all these documents was no longer an issue because of the fact that we had made a full answer and this was a legal question in terms of whether we were or we're not doing business.","start":458.769,"stop":481.957,"duration":23.19},{"text":"But on our refusal to -- the Court refused to grant this motion and on our refusal to give all the names of our members, the Court adjudged us in contempt and find --","start":481.957,"stop":497.875,"duration":15.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you tender to the Court all the documents except for the members of it?","start":497.875,"stop":502.013,"duration":4.14}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Not yet, Your Honor.","start":502.013,"stop":503.752,"duration":1.74},{"text":"We didn't do that, Your Honor.","start":503.752,"stop":505.992,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Either I -- I want to be sure.","start":505.992,"stop":507.397,"duration":1.4},{"text":"I heard Mr. Carter to say, did you express readiness to file?","start":507.397,"stop":513.004,"duration":5.61}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":513.004,"stop":513.523,"duration":0.52},{"text":"We not only expressed readiness, we had secured the forms and attached them to our -- to our answer.","start":513.523,"stop":518.673,"duration":5.15}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And still not all of the -- all the things?","start":518.673,"stop":521.138,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, we have.","start":521.138,"stop":522.111,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Was there anything or are there items in the forms which you were unrelated to, to which you're not willing to respond?","start":522.111,"stop":528.948,"duration":6.84}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, the only thing that the form requires them, Mr. Justice Frankfurter, is that you file your articles of incorporation which incidentally the State already had.","start":528.948,"stop":540.032,"duration":11.08},{"text":"They were attached to the complaint which was filed by the Attorney General and that you designate your place of business which the State knew because it's so designated in the bill of complaint and indicating agent for service, these things we do.","start":540.032,"stop":555.739,"duration":15.71}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, do you mean Mr. Carter that, ordinarily, a foreign corporation needs to do more -- no more than that?","start":555.739,"stop":562.371,"duration":6.63},{"text":"Is that the case in Alabama?","start":562.371,"stop":563.857,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"As we understand the law.","start":563.857,"stop":565.667,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) in answer to Mr. Justice Frankfurter's question, you said you had filled out those forms?","start":565.667,"stop":573.953,"duration":8.29}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"We secured them from the -- from the Secretary of State and attached them to our answer and indicating --","start":573.953,"stop":580.95,"duration":7}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":580.95,"stop":582.447,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"We filled them out.","start":582.447,"stop":583.493,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"You admit that you did have a place of business in Alabama?","start":583.493,"stop":586.914,"duration":3.42}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"We -- we have a southeast regional office in Birmingham which was maintained by (Inaudible).","start":586.914,"stop":593.232,"duration":6.32}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you admit that -- therein that you're doing business in Alabama?","start":593.232,"stop":596.883,"duration":3.65}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"We are contesting as I attempt to make it, Your Honor.","start":596.883,"stop":600.235,"duration":3.35},{"text":"Our contention was that we do not think that we are doing business in Alabama.","start":600.235,"stop":605.758,"duration":5.52},{"text":"We do not think that we're doing business in Alabama and we do not think that this law applies, but we were willing to waive and comply with the law and therefore we proceeded to attempt to domestic.","start":605.758,"stop":619.791,"duration":14.03},{"text":"Now, we've indicated that we would file these forms if the Court would permit as to do.","start":619.791,"stop":624.051,"duration":4.26},{"text":"The Court had indicated that we could not even make any attempts to write this.","start":624.051,"stop":628.183,"duration":4.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Carter, did this filled out form bear the name of any person and the signature?","start":628.183,"stop":635.786,"duration":7.6}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"It was the -- the form was filled out by the -- by the organization.","start":635.786,"stop":640.959,"duration":5.17},{"text":"I think it has to be signed by the President.","start":640.959,"stop":642.733,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But was it -- what I want to know.","start":642.733,"stop":644.45,"duration":1.72},{"text":"Was there -- was there in that form appears the name of any person or persons?","start":644.45,"stop":650.222,"duration":5.77}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"It appears the name of the --","start":650.222,"stop":652.11,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Person.","start":652.11,"stop":652.838,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"The person, I believe.","start":652.838,"stop":653.992,"duration":1.15},{"text":"Now, I can't be sure of this but let me say this that whatever was required in terms of the form, we did it and I -- I'm not really clear as to whether or not the name appear by -- as I remember.","start":653.992,"stop":667.649,"duration":13.66},{"text":"The -- the name of the president of the corporation has to be signed.","start":667.649,"stop":671.345,"duration":3.7}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"My question has pertinence as you will doubt as well as infer from what is required and what may be required -- or may not be required in the disclosure, that's why I'm asking.","start":671.345,"stop":685.324,"duration":13.98}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, as I indicated, when we continued to -- to refuse, to divulge the names of our members pursuant to our -- we were fined, adjudged in contempt and fined $10,000 with a proviso that we did not comply within five days and the fine would be $100,000.","start":685.324,"stop":706.457,"duration":21.13},{"text":"Now, on July 20 --","start":706.457,"stop":707.866,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Was -- was it -- was there any trading by the judge or was there any statement of what the $10,000 fine was for or against?","start":707.866,"stop":718.384,"duration":10.52}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think we have cited the order of -- of the judge, if the Court pleases, in the record.","start":718.384,"stop":728.398,"duration":10.01},{"text":"All I can say is that the judge indicates before the -- our refusal to submit the names as of July 25.","start":728.398,"stop":738.137,"duration":9.74},{"text":"We were fined $10,000 and adjudged in contempt.","start":738.137,"stop":741.776,"duration":3.64},{"text":"If we did not comply --","start":741.776,"stop":744.44,"duration":2.66}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That is if you continued to disobey.","start":744.44,"stop":747.77,"duration":3.33},{"text":"That's what the $100,000 for?","start":747.77,"stop":749.391,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":749.391,"stop":749.94,"duration":0.55},{"text":"Now, this is cited as --","start":749.94,"stop":754.008,"duration":4.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Because the $10,000 fine must have been for the refusal.","start":754.008,"stop":757.799,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":757.799,"stop":758.818,"duration":1.02},{"text":"They -- they were cited at page 13 on -- of the -- at the appendix 13 (a) of the appendix to the petition for writ of certiorari in the record.","start":758.818,"stop":767.259,"duration":8.44}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you very much.","start":767.259,"stop":771.194,"duration":3.93}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, on July 30 which is four days afterwards, we came into the trial court with a motion to vacate, stay or set aside the Court's contempt order.","start":771.194,"stop":784.408,"duration":13.21},{"text":"And at that time, Mr. Justice Burton, we tendered compliance with the order of the Court with the exception of the -- the prior portion of the order requiring us to give the names and addresses of our members and a portion of the order which asked us to submit all of our files, all of our letters, all of our correspondents and so forth which we contended was burdensome and would completely disrupt our operation.","start":784.408,"stop":812.88,"duration":28.47}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you're purging yourself of all the contempt except on the member's list.","start":812.88,"stop":816.83,"duration":3.95}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":816.83,"stop":817.746,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":817.746,"stop":820.769,"duration":3.02}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"I didn't hear you, sir.","start":820.769,"stop":822.94,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":822.94,"stop":834.775,"duration":11.83}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":834.775,"stop":835.989,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":835.989,"stop":841.904,"duration":5.91}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":841.904,"stop":842.408,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"In which to comply.","start":842.408,"stop":844.793,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":844.793,"stop":845.382,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"And on the 30th, you did tender all the materials required by the order (Inaudible).","start":845.382,"stop":852.249,"duration":6.87}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir and I -- as I indicated in that item, all of which required us to submit all of our files and so forth, which we could properly -- we could not comply with and we indicated that into the Court.","start":852.249,"stop":863.549,"duration":11.3},{"text":"This was just physically impossible for us to do and we so said -- said this in our -- in our motion.","start":863.549,"stop":869.532,"duration":5.98}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"And mostly denied on the next day, the 31st of July.","start":869.532,"stop":872.843,"duration":3.31}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":872.843,"stop":873.305,"duration":0.46},{"text":"That was denied on July 30.","start":873.305,"stop":876.824,"duration":3.52}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Same -- same date?","start":876.824,"stop":877.748,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":877.748,"stop":878.053,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"July 30?","start":878.053,"stop":878.775,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":878.775,"stop":881.22,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In the -- the interlocutory decree, there was an ex parte -- that was ex parte, wasn't it?","start":881.22,"stop":887.614,"duration":6.39}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":887.614,"stop":888.345,"duration":0.73},{"text":"The -- temporary (Voice Overlap) --","start":888.345,"stop":889.906,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- ex parte proceeding --","start":889.906,"stop":891.081,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"The temporary restraining order --","start":891.081,"stop":892.575,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, now did that restrain you -- didn't that restrain you from doing any business?","start":892.575,"stop":896.338,"duration":3.76}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"It restrained us from doing business and yes.","start":896.338,"stop":899.401,"duration":3.06}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All together?","start":899.401,"stop":900.096,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":900.096,"stop":900.503,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It wasn't merely a dislocation, but you were restrained from doing any business?","start":900.503,"stop":904.541,"duration":4.04}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":904.541,"stop":905.307,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"On ex parte.","start":905.307,"stop":908.146,"duration":2.84}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"And from doing any business, from soliciting, from maintaining any chapters and holding any meetings in Alabama and from carrying on any activities in Alabama.","start":908.146,"stop":918.69,"duration":10.54},{"text":"That would be as (Voice Overlap) --","start":918.69,"stop":918.859,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that tied you completely.","start":918.859,"stop":920.846,"duration":1.99},{"text":"That immobilized you until the restraining order came on -- if it did come on for a hearing.","start":920.846,"stop":927.254,"duration":6.41},{"text":"Is that right?","start":927.254,"stop":927.74,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"It never came on for it.","start":927.74,"stop":928.844,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It never came.","start":928.844,"stop":929.469,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":929.469,"stop":930.191,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But did you continue under the restraint of that until the contempt proceeding?","start":930.191,"stop":934.113,"duration":3.92}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"We did -- we obeyed the order that is that we notified our affiliates that the order was enforced and we had no meetings and we did nothing to disobey the order.","start":934.113,"stop":944.879,"duration":10.77}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What I want to know is when did the -- when did the obligation of that restraining order seized?","start":944.879,"stop":951.61,"duration":6.73},{"text":"When is that --","start":951.61,"stop":952.45,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- the restraining order is still in effect.","start":952.45,"stop":955.54,"duration":3.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But the restraining order continued to run and runs to this moment.","start":955.54,"stop":958.537,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir, because -- because of the fact that we -- because we are in contempt under Alabama law, we have no right to proceed on the merits of the restraining order.","start":958.537,"stop":972.323,"duration":13.79},{"text":"Our motion to dissolve was never heard so that the restraining order has been in effect, ex parte since June 1st, 1956.","start":972.323,"stop":981.454,"duration":9.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Let's see if I understand that.","start":981.454,"stop":982.48,"duration":1.03},{"text":"According to Alabama law, whether it's the decision of the statute, it doesn't make any difference.","start":982.48,"stop":987.824,"duration":5.34},{"text":"According to Alabama law, a restraining order, putting new for the time being out of business completely, continues and has not been reviewed or it has not been considered for the view -- to setting it aside and making it permanent because in the meantime -- in the meantime, the State moved disclosure and you did not fully satisfy the requirement of disclosure granted by the judge.","start":987.824,"stop":1019.996,"duration":32.17},{"text":"You offered some compliance, but not all of it.","start":1019.996,"stop":1022.969,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1022.969,"stop":1023.521,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It thereupon cast you in contempt and that -- that as it was suspended any action on the restraining order except that the restraining order still restrained you.Is that the situation?","start":1023.521,"stop":1032.675,"duration":9.15}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- that's the situation precisely.","start":1032.675,"stop":1035.179,"duration":2.5}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What happened to this provision requiring (Inaudible) the fund, is that State or something?","start":1035.179,"stop":1040.396,"duration":5.22}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"The provision with respect to the -- the State has made no effort to collect the fund.","start":1040.396,"stop":1047.067,"duration":6.67},{"text":"We don't have -- the fact of the matter is, we have no funds in Alabama and there are some questions as to whether or not under the conflict rules of Alabama could collect the -- the money, but I think that Alabama has accomplished its purpose which was to get at that business and put us out of Alabama and the State has not proceeded to file (Voice Overlap) --","start":1047.067,"stop":1068.087,"duration":21.02}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Why is it your motion to dissolve was never heard?","start":1068.087,"stop":1071.284,"duration":3.2}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, when we filed that motion to dissolve on July the 2nd, it was set down for hearing on July 17th.","start":1071.284,"stop":1082.885,"duration":11.6},{"text":"On July 5, the State comes in and says for us to disclose our members.","start":1082.885,"stop":1089.876,"duration":6.99},{"text":"On July 9, that was heard and granted.","start":1089.876,"stop":1093.094,"duration":3.22},{"text":"When we refused to the hearing on these objections and so forth, the court continued the hearing that the -- time for us comply and then continue the hearing on a motion to dissolve so it would be behind the hearing on the -- on the question of whether or not we were to comply with the order.","start":1093.094,"stop":1110.939,"duration":17.85}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Then they say they'll not hear it unless you comply with the order.","start":1110.939,"stop":1113.263,"duration":2.32}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1113.263,"stop":1114.147,"duration":0.88},{"text":"That was -- that's the -- the exact result of what's going on.","start":1114.147,"stop":1117.406,"duration":3.26}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me ask you this.","start":1117.406,"stop":1118.346,"duration":0.94},{"text":"Under Alabama law, supposed you were to pay the $100,000 because you continued in recalcitrance and disobedience, and referred yourself by performance, but paid the fine.","start":1118.346,"stop":1131.624,"duration":13.28},{"text":"Is the restraining order, the motion to dissolve not appealable?","start":1131.624,"stop":1136.087,"duration":4.46}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would say --","start":1136.087,"stop":1137.319,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In short, there is this extensive restraining order.","start":1137.319,"stop":1142.306,"duration":4.99},{"text":"In the meantime, the State asked for some disclosure and you feel that that's the thing you shouldn't disclose and you stand part on that.","start":1142.306,"stop":1151.107,"duration":8.8},{"text":"Does that mean you have to live under that restraining order continuously?","start":1151.107,"stop":1155.934,"duration":4.83}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Apparently so, Your Honor, because it may well be that if we would have paid the $100,000 that we would be considered purge of contempt, but then we will be ordered to comply with the order and we could be found in contempt again until the whole thing would go on.","start":1155.934,"stop":1173.917,"duration":17.98}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean the discovery order?","start":1173.917,"stop":1175.555,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, the discovery.","start":1175.555,"stop":1175.892,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"You -- you still have --","start":1175.892,"stop":1177.311,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir, the discovery order, the interlocutory.","start":1177.311,"stop":1182.288,"duration":4.98}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Is this a civil contempt order that is purgeable or is this an outright fine as to a criminal contempt?","start":1182.288,"stop":1191.446,"duration":9.16}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"The Supreme Court of Alabama has held that its civil contempt.","start":1191.446,"stop":1195.991,"duration":4.55},{"text":"We --","start":1195.991,"stop":1196.086,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1196.086,"stop":1197.151,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon.","start":1197.151,"stop":1197.597,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And therefore is perjury.","start":1197.597,"stop":1199.579,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"The Supreme Court has held -- of Alabama has held that it's -- it's a civil contempt.","start":1199.579,"stop":1203.745,"duration":4.17},{"text":"If it were a criminal contempt, the fine could have -- could only be $50 so that the Supreme Court has held that it's -- we contend it under the law of Alabama that -- and some of the cases of the Supreme Court that this should be considered as criminal contempt and the fine of $50.","start":1203.745,"stop":1220.839,"duration":17.09},{"text":"But in this opinion, the Supreme Court disagrees and holds that it is civil contempt.","start":1220.839,"stop":1225.661,"duration":4.82}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, $100,000 -- this isn't a bargain.You don't say you can either obey or pay $100,000.","start":1225.661,"stop":1231.733,"duration":6.07},{"text":"It isn't that kind of --","start":1231.733,"stop":1233.656,"duration":1.92}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":1233.656,"stop":1233.901,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I can't imagine it.","start":1233.901,"stop":1236.865,"duration":2.96}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, on the -- with this -- on July 10 that I -- that I can recapture the sequence of event, this motion was denied.","start":1236.865,"stop":1254.518,"duration":17.65},{"text":"We then went to the Supreme Court of Alabama with a motion to stay or satisfy the -- the order of the lower court pending review on certiorari, pending the filing or disposition of a petition for certiorari in the Supreme Court.","start":1254.518,"stop":1269.434,"duration":14.92}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"This was to satisfy the order of contempt.","start":1269.434,"stop":1271.948,"duration":2.51}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, to hold the order of contempt that's set to -- to set it aside in State, throughout the State for the proceedings or set it aside until we had an opportunity to file a petition for writ of certiorari in the Supreme Court of Alabama.","start":1271.948,"stop":1286.28,"duration":14.33},{"text":"The Supreme Court of Alabama on July 31st, we had a hearing before the Court, ruled that the only way for the Supreme Court to review contempt adjudications was on certiorari, but since we have not filed the petition for certiorari that it did not considered that it could interfere the action of the Court insofar as the contempt of adjudication is concerned.","start":1286.28,"stop":1309.901,"duration":23.62},{"text":"At that point and even before this decision was handed down, the Circuit Court issued its second order of contempt which find -- found that we have failed to comply within five days and found this in further contempt and fined us for $100,000.","start":1309.901,"stop":1327.372,"duration":17.47},{"text":"On August the 8th, we filed a petition for writ of certiorari in the Supreme Court of Alabama.","start":1327.372,"stop":1334.239,"duration":6.87},{"text":"This was denied as insufficient after hearing on August the 13th.","start":1334.239,"stop":1339.432,"duration":5.19},{"text":"We filed another petition on August 20 and that petition was -- the opinion was handed down which is the -- which is in the record here.","start":1339.432,"stop":1349.112,"duration":9.68}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What was the ground of insufficiency on the first petition for certiorari?","start":1349.112,"stop":1352.747,"duration":3.63}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Justice Harlan, I -- I am not clear.","start":1352.747,"stop":1355.81,"duration":3.06},{"text":"I think it was technically that we had failed to put in the petition, certain allegations which we have set forth fully in our brief, but they held that we hadn't technically complied with their rules.","start":1355.81,"stop":1369.461,"duration":13.65},{"text":"Now, in its opinion on December 6, the Supreme Court of Alabama refused to grant the petition for writ of certiorari on the ground that if we had desire to seek a review on the merits of the order to disclose, the interlocutory order to disclose, that the proper method for us to sought such a review was by petition for writ of mandamus.","start":1369.461,"stop":1393.699,"duration":24.24},{"text":"That on certiorari, adjudications of contempt on certiorari that the Court is concerned only to jurisdictional matter that it has to find that the order is void on its face that there is no jurisdiction of the parties or that contempt was not in fact committed or that the citation was in someway insufficient.","start":1393.699,"stop":1417.465,"duration":23.77},{"text":"And the court found jurisdictionally and so forth that this case met all these requirements and therefore that the Circuit Court had the authority to find us in contempt in a jurisdiction and then in addition, but even though it said we don't have to, the court went to the merits of the order and held that on the merits, the court below had the authority to issue the order itself.","start":1417.465,"stop":1440.685,"duration":23.22},{"text":"Now, we are -- we therefore feel that the very outside of these proceedings were met with the question of whether this Court has jurisdiction and we think that it unquestionably had.","start":1440.685,"stop":1454.649,"duration":13.96},{"text":"We -- we take that position as we have indicated in our brief under the authority of Rogers versus Alabama.","start":1454.649,"stop":1461.446,"duration":6.8}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Carter, will you clear me up on this.","start":1461.446,"stop":1464.13,"duration":2.68},{"text":"You read the Supreme Court's opinion as saying initially that this should have been by way of mandamus, not certiorari.","start":1464.13,"stop":1472.301,"duration":8.17}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"On to -- to raise the issues that we won't raise.","start":1472.301,"stop":1473.992,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1473.992,"stop":1474.929,"duration":0.94},{"text":"Yes, but then after having decided that the Circuit Court did have jurisdiction, treating as within those limits under certiorari then went on to deal with the merits.","start":1474.929,"stop":1485.584,"duration":10.65},{"text":"Is that to say that the merits were dealt with as if you had applied for mandamus?","start":1485.584,"stop":1489.808,"duration":4.22}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1489.808,"stop":1490.605,"duration":0.8},{"text":"The Court -- well, I've tend to take the position that that's what happened, but the -- but to no offense to the Supreme Court of Alabama and all honesty so far as this decision was concerned, it said that although we don't have to go for it and we can stop after we find that the court has jurisdiction and -- and --","start":1490.605,"stop":1510.221,"duration":19.62}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, my question is they could have stopped in suggesting that the court in fact went on and dealt with the merits.","start":1510.221,"stop":1516.747,"duration":6.53}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1516.747,"stop":1517.19,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, in dealing with the merits, did the court do what it would have done had you come up by way of mandamus?","start":1517.19,"stop":1522.42,"duration":5.23}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"We think so.","start":1522.42,"stop":1523.836,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"But the Court said that you're doing it because you didn't file mandamus?","start":1523.836,"stop":1528.553,"duration":4.72}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"The Court said that we don't have to do anything further, but it went on and said that on the merits of the order, the order is valid and should be sustained.","start":1528.553,"stop":1538.809,"duration":10.26},{"text":"We think in -- in an answer to Mr. Justice Brennan said, we think that in effect, the Court indicated that if we had come upon that damage, it would have sustained the order on the merits, but that's the substance of the opinion.","start":1538.809,"stop":1551.301,"duration":12.49}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, Mr. Carter, if you, conscientiously and unquestioningly, concluded that under Alabama law, these should have been raised on mandamus.","start":1551.301,"stop":1564.155,"duration":12.85},{"text":"That was your clear conviction.","start":1564.155,"stop":1566.782,"duration":2.63},{"text":"Then, you would think the State Court decided it on a state ground which if you sought that.","start":1566.782,"stop":1572.428,"duration":5.65}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":1572.428,"stop":1573.145,"duration":0.72},{"text":"I -- the reason I say, “No, sir” is because if I remember a decision of this Court in Thomas versus Collins where this same kind of thing was done, I think that this Court said that even though the Court indicated that it did not have to go into the merits, since it did go into the merits, the issue was here.","start":1573.145,"stop":1590.726,"duration":17.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1590.726,"stop":1591.407,"duration":0.68},{"text":"I understand.","start":1591.407,"stop":1592.065,"duration":0.66},{"text":"If they said we decide it, but I thought this depends on Justice Brennan that you said you had honestly to say that they said we don't indeed, although we talk about this thing.","start":1592.065,"stop":1603.078,"duration":11.01},{"text":"We really go in that ground.","start":1603.078,"stop":1604.339,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1604.339,"stop":1604.659,"duration":0.32},{"text":"Well, that's -- that's true.","start":1604.659,"stop":1605.892,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1605.892,"stop":1606.209,"duration":0.32},{"text":"Now, if you thought that's the ground they went on and if you thought they were right about that ground then it would be a state ground.","start":1606.209,"stop":1612.829,"duration":6.62}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, yes.","start":1612.829,"stop":1614.574,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that right?","start":1614.574,"stop":1615.206,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1615.206,"stop":1615.727,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right, but -- but your contention is that that isn't so.","start":1615.727,"stop":1619.092,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1619.092,"stop":1619.503,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":1619.503,"stop":1623.517,"duration":4.01}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"We -- as we indicated in our petition for writ of certiorari, we think that what Alabama has done is to seek here too unfairly, to seek our right to have this -- this case reviewed for federal rights which we think are here under the guides of local practice.","start":1623.517,"stop":1644.134,"duration":20.62}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"I can't find it's too late to seek by mandamus.","start":1644.134,"stop":1647.483,"duration":3.35}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"We think so although, Mr. Justice Burton.","start":1647.483,"stop":1650.583,"duration":3.1},{"text":"There are some decisions in Alabama where a person has come up to the Supreme Court on a petition for writ of certiorari or petition for writ of mandamus and the Court said, “You've taken the wrong proceeding, but we will treat it as a -- as the proper proceeding as a petition for writ of mandamus.”","start":1650.583,"stop":1666.153,"duration":15.57},{"text":"They did not do it here so that --","start":1666.153,"stop":1668.305,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Carter, we were to agree with your interpretation of what was done here.","start":1668.305,"stop":1673.717,"duration":5.41},{"text":"Would you then now have to argue the question you are about to argue?","start":1673.717,"stop":1679.669,"duration":5.95},{"text":"This is not an ultimate ground --","start":1679.669,"stop":1681.852,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1681.852,"stop":1682.662,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that they unfairly, under the guidance of state practice (Inaudible).","start":1682.662,"stop":1686.522,"duration":3.86}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1686.522,"stop":1688.205,"duration":1.68},{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1688.205,"stop":1688.433,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We don't even get to it if we agree with your first.","start":1688.433,"stop":1690.691,"duration":2.26}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1690.691,"stop":1694.314,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"In Alabama, are petitions for certiorari ever treated as petitions for mandamus and decided on that basis by the Supreme Court.","start":1694.314,"stop":1705.256,"duration":10.94}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- there is a case and the only case I know of quite frankly which was decided where -- in which a -- an Alabama -- I think it was in (Inaudible), it went to the Supreme Court of Alabama on a petition for writ of mandamus.","start":1705.256,"stop":1727.094,"duration":21.84},{"text":"The Court held that this should have been from contempt on a petition for writ of certiorari.","start":1727.094,"stop":1732.114,"duration":5.02},{"text":"But since you've asked for such further relief, we're going to grant -- we're going to treat it as a petition, as a proper petition and I -- I think I can cite that case for you to.","start":1732.114,"stop":1749.389,"duration":17.27},{"text":"It is Armstrong versus Green which is cited at 60 S. 2d 834.","start":1749.389,"stop":1756.851,"duration":7.46},{"text":"We do not cite it in our brief.","start":1756.851,"stop":1761.325,"duration":4.47},{"text":"Now --","start":1761.325,"stop":1762.542,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Your contention is that a fair reading of Alabama cases makes clear that as a matter of facts, on certiorari it does go beyond for mere technical questions of jurisdiction.","start":1762.542,"stop":1773.382,"duration":10.84}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"There's no question.","start":1773.382,"stop":1774.226,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's your position.","start":1774.226,"stop":1775.037,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1775.037,"stop":1775.672,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And since that's Alabama law in other cases, they can't refuse it in a case involving a federal right.","start":1775.672,"stop":1781.293,"duration":5.62}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1781.293,"stop":1782.087,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's your position.","start":1782.087,"stop":1782.795,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's our -- that's our position that -- that under Alabama law, the -- the same kind of questions that we have here which go to the validity of the order, disobedience of which led to the citation of contempt and which raised constitutional questions involved, Alabama has decided those cases on petition for writ of certiorari from contempt.","start":1782.795,"stop":1805.866,"duration":23.07},{"text":"And in fact, we go further insofar as we understood Alabama law, this was the customary way in which issues of this kind were raised and treated.","start":1805.866,"stop":1817.115,"duration":11.25},{"text":"And, so that we think that under the -- we've decided the case which we think are in point in our petition for writ of certiorari in Alabama law and we think that the Court has jurisdiction.","start":1817.115,"stop":1832.092,"duration":14.98},{"text":"Now, before I go into the argument of the merits, I think it's best for me to try to recapitulate what I think are the orders which are before the Court and before this Court which we ought to review.","start":1832.092,"stop":1846.049,"duration":13.96},{"text":"We think that the temporary restraining order which is involved in this case, which barred us from all activities and in fact ousted us from the State, and barred us in complying with the law, the interlocutory order requiring us, among other things, to disclose the identification and the addresses of our members.","start":1846.049,"stop":1867.046,"duration":21},{"text":"The first adjudication of contempt and the fine of $10,000 which was entered on July 25, the second adjudication of contempt in the fine of $100,000 which was issued on July 31, and the order and judgment of the Supreme Court of Alabama denying the petition -- our petition for writ of certiorari.","start":1867.046,"stop":1887.303,"duration":20.26}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"How far does it lead from contempt?","start":1887.303,"stop":1890.269,"duration":2.97}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"I didn't hear you, sir.","start":1890.269,"stop":1891.255,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1891.255,"stop":1895.903,"duration":4.65}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1895.903,"stop":1897.269,"duration":1.37},{"text":"This is the -- I -- I meant that when I said that the order and judgment of the Supreme Court of Alabama in -- in this case, that's the opinion here.","start":1897.269,"stop":1906.351,"duration":9.08}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the one thing that is actually here on -- under your proceeding, isn't it?","start":1906.351,"stop":1910.373,"duration":4.02}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":1910.373,"stop":1911.289,"duration":0.92},{"text":"Yes, that -- that opinion is -- is here on (Inaudible) --","start":1911.289,"stop":1914.138,"duration":2.85}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what we (Inaudible) --","start":1914.138,"stop":1916.98,"duration":2.84}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1916.98,"stop":1917.134,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that decision.","start":1917.134,"stop":1917.926,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, sir.","start":1917.926,"stop":1918.509,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"It's not the rest.","start":1918.509,"stop":1920.03,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we think that the rest --","start":1920.03,"stop":1921.59,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Harold Burton","textObjs":[{"text":"It may be involved in that.","start":1921.59,"stop":1923.11,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"We think that the rest is here and I -- if I'm -- I would -- if permitted, I would like to indicate how in a moment.","start":1923.11,"stop":1933.138,"duration":10.03},{"text":"It's our contention that the entire proceedings in Alabama are void that the -- that the -- the Alabama authorities had no -- no authority and no power and no -- to oust us from the State.","start":1933.138,"stop":1947.639,"duration":14.5},{"text":"That we have been deprived the right to carry on our lawful -- lawful activities pursuant to a temporary restraining order, the order to disclose the list of our members and it is contempt to adjudications.","start":1947.639,"stop":1960.815,"duration":13.18},{"text":"We contend that the order requiring us to disclose the list of our members is a denial of our right, the right of the corporation and the right of its members to free speech and freedom of association and as protected by the First Amendment.","start":1960.815,"stop":1974.845,"duration":14.03},{"text":"We contend that if we have disclosed the list of our members, they would have been subjected to possible harm, threats, and fears.We further contend that the punishment for contempt and the fines issued was so vindictive that they in and of themselves, an excess -- that in and of itself constitute as a denial of due process.","start":1974.845,"stop":1998.793,"duration":23.95},{"text":"And that the atmosphere in Alabama which was one of open hostility to our organization and -- and its members that this has so insinuated itself into the proceedings in the Court that we think that the whole proceedings below was in fact a perversion of the judicial process.","start":1998.793,"stop":2020.985,"duration":22.19},{"text":"Now, with respect to the free speech contentions, it's our view that as an organization whose purpose is to seek to improve the status of Negroes in America and to remove color discrimination, that we are to pursue this objective in a lawful manner, and that we are entitled, and our members are entitled to associate together to pursue this objective and that we have the protection of the Constitution of the United States in so doing.","start":2020.985,"stop":2059.248,"duration":38.26},{"text":"Now, it is true that under the present status of affairs in Alabama that at the present time, our aims are at bearings with the -- with State policy, but the aims of -- and the objectives of the organization which are to remove racial and color discrimination from American life are in accord with the -- with the rights, privileges and immunities guaranteed under the Federal Constitution.","start":2059.248,"stop":2093.721,"duration":34.47},{"text":"And although Alabama in a desire to maintain segregation and so forth, we think that we have a right to pursue our objectives of the removal of segregation, even though it would be a bearing with the State policy and that the State policy in this regard has no effect whatever.","start":2093.721,"stop":2115.433,"duration":21.71},{"text":"Now, insofar as our members are concerned in the right of the organization to do this, it is our belief that under the -- the decisions of this Court that our members in the organization are entitled to pursue these objectives free and unsighted from any State control, acts compelling justification.","start":2115.433,"stop":2138.413,"duration":22.98},{"text":"We think that's what the decision in this Court hold and we think that that has been repeated in the two latest decisions that we know of on the subject decided last term, Sweezy and Watkins.","start":2138.413,"stop":2153.33,"duration":14.92},{"text":"Now, we do not -- we do not contend of course that the State may not control the organization and may not limit its activities in some way, but we do -- we do contend that whereas here, First Amendment rights are being invaded that the balance has to be struck between the necessity for the regulation and the freedom which has to -- which we feel we're entitled to have.","start":2153.33,"stop":2182.78,"duration":29.45},{"text":"Alabama has offered no justification whatever in any -- in any paper filed in this case to warrant the -- the restraints issued or to warrant the order with regard to our members.","start":2182.78,"stop":2199.859,"duration":17.08},{"text":"There is no necessity, no need that has been shown as to why this -- the Attorney General desires to know who our members are.","start":2199.859,"stop":2207.775,"duration":7.92},{"text":"No purpose would be served by it, in fact, what would happen insofar we are concerned with this is that the status spreading on the ground which has no right to trail.","start":2207.775,"stop":2217.711,"duration":9.94},{"text":"Now --","start":2217.711,"stop":2217.99,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry if I interrupt you.","start":2217.99,"stop":2219.546,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Surely.","start":2219.546,"stop":2219.932,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose I might find out the answer to this (Inaudible).","start":2219.932,"stop":2228.077,"duration":8.15},{"text":"Do you claim that it was not within the power of the trial court in sustaining this motion to produce, to require you to give the names and the addresses of your members, not within his power?","start":2228.077,"stop":2248.45,"duration":20.37},{"text":"Was that relevant in other words to the lawsuit pending before the Court as to whether or not you were doing business there and within the power of the trial court so to order?","start":2248.45,"stop":2260.902,"duration":12.45}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"We -- we think it was not.","start":2260.902,"stop":2263.02,"duration":2.12},{"text":"We think not only was it not relevant.","start":2263.02,"stop":2265.742,"duration":2.72},{"text":"We think that the trial court had no authority to order this disclosure because of the fact that our contention is that the right of our members to associate together in the organization, to associate together is -- is protected from enforced disclosure to any State authority.This is our contention.","start":2265.742,"stop":2286.648,"duration":20.91},{"text":"Now, on the question of relevance, if we think it is not a basic question, but on the question of relevance in -- in the light of our answer in which we had admitted that we had the kinds of operation that we have been carrying on, what we have been, the character of our -- of our operation, not only in the Alabama but throughout the United States, the question of who are members were have nothing and no relevance whatever to the -- the question which was purportedly before the court as to whether or not we were doing business.","start":2286.648,"stop":2319.742,"duration":33.09},{"text":"And besides that, when we offered to register and offered to waive our right to object to Alabama saying whether we were or we're not doing business, if there had been any relevance, we submit that it was lost at that point.","start":2319.742,"stop":2334.244,"duration":14.5},{"text":"There was no issue before the Court from which the -- the identification of our members had any relevance whatever.","start":2334.244,"stop":2340.974,"duration":6.73},{"text":"Does that answer your question?","start":2340.974,"stop":2347.397,"duration":6.42}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I think so.","start":2347.397,"stop":2352.827,"duration":5.43}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, it's our -- our theory that the only purpose of this order to disclose was in order that the Alabama Court and the -- the Attorney General was in fact seeking to use this so that we would be placed with two which we consider unconstitutional conditions.","start":2352.827,"stop":2391.412,"duration":38.58},{"text":"Either we have to comply with the order to disclose and therefore, submit to a violation of our right of free speech and right of free association, or we risk content and we are ousted from the State as we were and never get an opportunity to test the merits of the order.","start":2391.412,"stop":2412.097,"duration":20.69},{"text":"Now, in our view, the -- the respondents have sought to utilize the subversion cases and the Bryant versus Zimmerman which we think have no relevance whatsoever in this case.","start":2412.097,"stop":2430.566,"duration":18.47},{"text":"We're not -- we're not subversive.","start":2430.566,"stop":2434.561,"duration":4},{"text":"There is no allegation that we were subversive.","start":2434.561,"stop":2437.528,"duration":2.97},{"text":"There is no allegation in fact in the pleadings that -- that we have done anything illegal other than that we have been in Alabama according to the State's complaint without registering.","start":2437.528,"stop":2453.566,"duration":16.04},{"text":"And we think that these cases have no purpose here because in those cases where the Court felt that the State might require or the federal government might require some invasion of free speech that in those instances, the Court found that there was some justification for it which we contend the Court cannot find in this particular case.","start":2453.566,"stop":2481.397,"duration":27.83},{"text":"We feel that the -- and we think that the record shows that Alabama was using its Foreign Corporations Registration Act in this proceeding as a cloak to require conformance in the State on this issue of segregation as -- as oppose to anti-segregation.","start":2481.397,"stop":2503.918,"duration":22.52}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr Carter, I'm not sure that I know your position on the question of the duty to file a certificate with the Secretary of State if that's the official.","start":2503.918,"stop":2515.174,"duration":11.26}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":2515.174,"stop":2515.244,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose that was all that was in issue here, what would be your position?","start":2515.244,"stop":2520.082,"duration":4.84}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we don't think it is an issue any longer, but we don't think it is in issue.","start":2520.082,"stop":2523.87,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's because you profit the signing of it.","start":2523.87,"stop":2526.976,"duration":3.11},{"text":"That's because you are ready to file that?","start":2526.976,"stop":2529.071,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2529.071,"stop":2529.718,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So, that isn't before us then, is it?","start":2529.718,"stop":2531.428,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"We don't think so.","start":2531.428,"stop":2532.998,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":2532.998,"stop":2534.465,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"You wanted to file the -- pay the charges, the fees, registration fees and so forth at the same time?","start":2534.465,"stop":2541.086,"duration":6.62}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2541.086,"stop":2541.653,"duration":0.57},{"text":"We offer to comply insofar as the law is concerned.","start":2541.653,"stop":2544.344,"duration":2.69}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the reason for -- the reason why states want to have foreign corporation so-called to file their certificate is in order to protect their own citizens for various reasons, so as to know whom to sue.","start":2544.344,"stop":2559.758,"duration":15.41}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2559.758,"stop":2560.093,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, you have your membership corporation, which mean that you're doing business without profit and therefore, the restriction or the qualifications are different in New York from what they have forbidden.","start":2560.093,"stop":2570.199,"duration":10.11},{"text":"If you raised this file and if the State has a right or at least there is nothing in the Federal Constitution to bar Louisiana -- Alabama from saying, “You must file a certificate,” because if you are engaged in any kind of activity, have an office, you rent something.","start":2570.199,"stop":2589.081,"duration":18.88},{"text":"You may owe the landlord or you're -- the conditions maybe in -- in such order, that order that the licensee coming in therefore and sue somebody, and they have the right to know whom to sue, who's responsible.","start":2589.081,"stop":2602.109,"duration":13.03},{"text":"Is that right?","start":2602.109,"stop":2602.252,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir..","start":2602.252,"stop":2602.933,"duration":0.68},{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2602.933,"stop":2603.699,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So that there is a distinction that I'd like to put it here, between requiring -- I'm not saying what the legal consequence is.","start":2603.699,"stop":2614.078,"duration":10.38},{"text":"There is a distinction between Alabama's right to say, “You give us the names of your officers, and you give us the names of people scattered all over Alabama which support your cost.”","start":2614.078,"stop":2625.158,"duration":11.08},{"text":"Isn't that?","start":2625.158,"stop":2625.779,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"I think so.","start":2625.779,"stop":2626.916,"duration":1.14},{"text":"I -- I think that in Alabama -- all Alabama requires for persons to domesticate are that they file their articles of a corporation which lists the persons that are incorporated and I -- and I believe the members of the Board of Directors that --","start":2626.916,"stop":2647.486,"duration":20.57}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The responsible people.","start":2647.486,"stop":2648.631,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":2648.631,"stop":2649.786,"duration":1.16},{"text":"Now --","start":2649.786,"stop":2650.267,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You have no objection to that, do you?","start":2650.267,"stop":2651.712,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":2651.712,"stop":2652.649,"duration":0.94},{"text":"We -- we don't -- we offered to -- to comply and the reason I -- I think that all of this is, even if we take the position and concede that Alabama had the right to request us to do that, we think that they have no authority to -- to use this as a jumping off ground to do the things that it had started and we say this for this reason.","start":2652.649,"stop":2681.262,"duration":28.61},{"text":"The -- the law in Alabama requiring foreign corporations to domesticate is to do precisely what you've indicated.","start":2681.262,"stop":2689.155,"duration":7.89},{"text":"Now, technically, admitting that we were doing business, technically only were we in violation because of the fact that Alabama knew our -- knew that we have a Southeast regional office.","start":2689.155,"stop":2703.014,"duration":13.86},{"text":"In fact of the matter is their tax is an exhibit to their complaint.","start":2703.014,"stop":2706.724,"duration":3.71},{"text":"They served the complaint on -- on us there.We submitted to the State's jurisdiction.","start":2706.724,"stop":2712.81,"duration":6.09},{"text":"There is no indication at all as between 1918 and 1956 and we have been -- had affiliates and had been doing the same thing in Alabama during that period of time that we -- in 1918 and 1956, that there was ever any effort by any Alabama citizen to sue the corporation which was defeated because we had not complied.","start":2712.81,"stop":2733.211,"duration":20.4}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but you don't argue Mr. Carter that failure to enforce the law for a period stops the sovereign from enforcement later.","start":2733.211,"stop":2740.597,"duration":7.39}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"We -- we don't argue that at all.","start":2740.597,"stop":2742.922,"duration":2.32},{"text":"We do think that it raises some presumption that this irreparable harm that's with no other contentions that this irreparable harm which the State alleged did not in fact takes place.","start":2742.922,"stop":2757.47,"duration":14.55}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"You -- do you -- is it -- did the Alabama Trial Court have legal authority to impose under the law of Alabama some penalty of whatsoever kind for the failure to comply within the time prescribed with an order to produce?","start":2757.47,"stop":2780.615,"duration":23.14}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean in order to produce the names and the address of our members?","start":2780.615,"stop":2783.864,"duration":3.25}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Did the trial court (Inaudible)?","start":2783.864,"stop":2794.11,"duration":10.25}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, assuming that the order is a valid order, Mr. Justice Whittaker.","start":2794.11,"stop":2801.297,"duration":7.19}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes, yes.","start":2801.297,"stop":2802.279,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"They have the -- they would have that now under content if we -- if we disobeyed it.","start":2802.279,"stop":2808.621,"duration":6.34},{"text":"As I understand Alabama law, if we -- as we disobey that order as any other order, we're contempt to Court.","start":2808.621,"stop":2814.322,"duration":5.7},{"text":"And the Court has the power to -- to enforce it by its contempt to adjudication, fine et cetera, but we don't think that they -- I don't know of any other power that they had in terms of this order that you are referring to.","start":2814.322,"stop":2827.416,"duration":13.09},{"text":"Let's assume that it was a valid order, but we don't contend that it was a valid order.","start":2827.416,"stop":2834.119,"duration":6.7},{"text":"I mean, that's our position.","start":2834.119,"stop":2835.718,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr Carter, may I get a little more light from you?","start":2835.718,"stop":2841.562,"duration":5.84},{"text":"It is Alabama law you say that when a -- when a -- what do you call that, restraining order is outstanding, if you don't obey it, if you don't obey and therefore it could be thrown into contempt.","start":2841.562,"stop":2859.104,"duration":17.54},{"text":"You can't raise the -- the validity or the scope of the restraining order.","start":2859.104,"stop":2866.034,"duration":6.93},{"text":"Is that right?","start":2866.034,"stop":2866.948,"duration":0.91},{"text":"That's what you say is Alabama law?","start":2866.948,"stop":2869.346,"duration":2.4}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if -- if at any time in the proceeding, if the Court pleases, as I understand Alabama law and I think that the Attorney General concedes this.","start":2869.346,"stop":2882.769,"duration":13.42},{"text":"If -- if at anytime in the proceeding, the result of this order, we are put in contempt then the whole proceedings is aborted, stopped --","start":2882.769,"stop":2893.167,"duration":10.4}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, go on.","start":2893.167,"stop":2894.271,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- whatever has happened remains and I would suspect that the Attorney General would then have the right to -- to obtain a default judgment and which will then perhaps make this appealable.","start":2894.271,"stop":2906.179,"duration":11.91}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But you say --","start":2906.179,"stop":2907.332,"duration":1.15}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"But we say not to --","start":2907.332,"stop":2907.632,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- you say that -- you say that that ordinary provision of Alabama law suspending a restraining order does not bar this Court from saying that you were thrown into contempt for disobeying a restraining order that was -- that exceeded the constitutional speed limit?","start":2907.632,"stop":2929.075,"duration":21.44}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2929.075,"stop":2929.591,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In that, they prohibited you from doing business when there was no relation between that protection given to Alabama and any interest of it under -- ensured that there was no possible irreparable damage that required such an extreme restriction of your right.","start":2929.591,"stop":2948.551,"duration":18.96},{"text":"Is that right?","start":2948.551,"stop":2949.051,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2949.051,"stop":2950.814,"duration":1.76}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Although -- although on a restraining order in ordinary instances, that might be alright.","start":2950.814,"stop":2958.11,"duration":7.3},{"text":"Now second, do you say that you're drawn in contempt because you disobeyed or build with discovery or whatever it's called, one of the features of which was the disclosure of your membership and that Alabama had no right to exact --","start":2958.11,"stop":2975.563,"duration":17.45}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":2975.563,"stop":2976.161,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Are those the two chief -- are those the two things?","start":2976.161,"stop":2978.673,"duration":2.51},{"text":"What else is there that you complain?","start":2978.673,"stop":2980.819,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we --","start":2980.819,"stop":2981.612,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So far as I understand, those are the two things.","start":2981.612,"stop":2983.233,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"So, we think that the contempt itself is so outrageous, but now I mean the --","start":2983.233,"stop":2988.257,"duration":5.02}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you mean the fine -- the amount?","start":2988.257,"stop":2989.305,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"A $100,000 fine.","start":2989.305,"stop":2990.782,"duration":1.48},{"text":"We think that's --","start":2990.782,"stop":2991.939,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, what do you say to the decision of this Court that obedience is due to an order even though a court may later be found to have improperly issued the order?","start":2991.939,"stop":3004.906,"duration":12.97}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"As -- as I understood that, that was the distinction that this Court made between criminal and civil contempt and that we have obeyed the temporary restraining order, so that we have not -- there is no public defiance of the -- of the Alabama court.","start":3004.906,"stop":3022.009,"duration":17.1},{"text":"We disobeyed the -- the order of -- ordering us to disclose because we thought that this was the only way that we can preserve our rights.","start":3022.009,"stop":3029.049,"duration":7.04}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And that is the only way you contest that.","start":3029.049,"stop":3031.206,"duration":2.16},{"text":"So that you're not within Louis case --","start":3031.206,"stop":3033.519,"duration":2.31}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":3033.519,"stop":3033.843,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and that, you didn't snap your fingers at the junction -- the injunctive process.","start":3033.843,"stop":3038.282,"duration":4.44}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":3038.282,"stop":3038.85,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But you are ordered to produce and you think you're ordered to produce something that the Constitution had no right to ask you to produce --","start":3038.85,"stop":3045.296,"duration":6.45}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":3045.296,"stop":3045.946,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and you stood your ground.","start":3045.946,"stop":3047.192,"duration":1.25},{"text":"Is that right?","start":3047.192,"stop":3047.71,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":3047.71,"stop":3048.953,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry to ask you some more questions.","start":3048.953,"stop":3052.856,"duration":3.9},{"text":"Do I correctly understand you to say to Justice Frankfurter that you're complaining of the temporary restraining order --","start":3052.856,"stop":3064.526,"duration":11.67}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3064.526,"stop":3065.048,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"-- as well as the finding of the contempt in which here is defined?","start":3065.048,"stop":3066.762,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"We --","start":3066.762,"stop":3069.009,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"From a particular provision of that restraining order.","start":3069.009,"stop":3071.7,"duration":2.69}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the -- we think that the court below has no juries -- that the court in effect acted arbitrarily, ousted us in Alabama.","start":3071.7,"stop":3078.988,"duration":7.29},{"text":"It had no jurisdiction, no authority to do this under the basis of this record.","start":3078.988,"stop":3083.769,"duration":4.78},{"text":"We think further if I -- if I may just finish.","start":3083.769,"stop":3087.5,"duration":3.73},{"text":"We -- we think further that the -- that the Supreme Court of Alabama sustained the authority of the Court to issue this temporary restraining order, even under the theory of the contempt which it had because it said that they have to be in jurisdiction in order for -- for -- it could have reviewed jurisdiction on certiorari.","start":3087.5,"stop":3108.401,"duration":20.9},{"text":"So the Supreme -- I'm sorry.","start":3108.401,"stop":3110.539,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) I'm asking you how you get the temporary injunction if there is no temporary restraining order -- temporary injunction as I understood (Inaudible) --","start":3110.539,"stop":3121.201,"duration":10.66}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3121.201,"stop":3122.15,"duration":0.95},{"text":"The (Voice Overlap) --","start":3122.15,"stop":3122.409,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) District Court or the trial court except by a motion to dissolve which was never heard and that all (Inaudible) was issued upon and probably were not, then you will properly cite the contempt to fine.","start":3122.409,"stop":3138.315,"duration":15.91}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the Supreme Court of Alabama had to necessarily, we thin, raise the issue of the temporary restraining order in that court.","start":3138.315,"stop":3148.304,"duration":9.99},{"text":"It held that the court below had jurisdiction to do what it did.","start":3148.304,"stop":3152.929,"duration":4.63},{"text":"Now, in so doing, we contend that it has to go to the question of whether the Court had the right to issue the temporary restraining order/ Otherwise, it would have to upheld that the order to produce constant with it was void.","start":3152.929,"stop":3167.607,"duration":14.68},{"text":"We think that this is very definitely before the Court, but not only as the temporary -- not only as the order to disclose in the contempt before the Court, but to go back to the initial thing that started the temporary restraining order itself.","start":3167.607,"stop":3181.865,"duration":14.26},{"text":"And -- and our contention is that all of these matters are here and that they should be disposed of by this Court.","start":3181.865,"stop":3196.336,"duration":14.47}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Rinehart.","start":3196.336,"stop":3200.058,"duration":3.72}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and members of the Court.","start":3200.058,"stop":3204.46,"duration":4.4},{"text":"Mr. Justice Whittaker's question is what I would like to concern myself with at the outset because it goes to the very heart of the case of what this Court has to review.","start":3204.46,"stop":3218.034,"duration":13.57},{"text":"Now, the opinion of the Supreme Court of Alabama deals with the Alabama law on certiorari in a limited review which that application or petition for that particular remedial writ is limited to, and that is jurisdiction of a person, jurisdiction of a subject matter, the regularity of the contempt proceedings, for example, whether there was a correct citation, whether there was even a hearing on this contempt.","start":3218.034,"stop":3255.599,"duration":37.57},{"text":"All of those things will be looked at on the face of the record.","start":3255.599,"stop":3261.047,"duration":5.45},{"text":"That is all that you get by certiorari and that's all this Court looked at.","start":3261.047,"stop":3269.177,"duration":8.13},{"text":"It is true and we do not deny that the Court then went on and discussed certain constitutional questions, not all of the constitutional questions which, Mr. Carter has discussed here, but certain of them, such as the question of a corporation's privilege against self-incrimination, whether a -- you can raise the rights of persons.","start":3269.177,"stop":3292.654,"duration":23.48},{"text":"In other words, whether certain of these rights are personal rights and you may not assert the right of another.","start":3292.654,"stop":3298.483,"duration":5.83},{"text":"Those things were discussed, but they there were not made the basis of the decision.","start":3298.483,"stop":3302.899,"duration":4.42},{"text":"They said mandamus was the proper way in which to review the order to produce and that a review of that order to produce was not before that court, and I would like to -- now, enter on a -- I hope I'm not too late with the discussion of the common law writs of mandamus in Alabama.","start":3302.899,"stop":3331.347,"duration":28.45},{"text":"It is the established law of Alabama that the review of interlocutory order of a Court of whatever nature is by writ of mandamus, petition I should say for writ of mandamus.Ex parte Hart which is cited in our brief, it is also cited in the opinion of the Court.","start":3331.347,"stop":3361.663,"duration":30.32},{"text":"This is -- I'm reading now from the record or transcript of record at page 25, an order requiring defendant to produce evidence in a pending clause maybe reviewed on petition for mandamus, Ex parte Hart, 240 Ala. 642.","start":3361.663,"stop":3379.658,"duration":17.99},{"text":"There is no lengthy discussion of the use of mandamus in that opinion.","start":3379.658,"stop":3385.923,"duration":6.26},{"text":"It was merely assumed that that was the proper way and it has always to my knowledge been the proper way to review in order to produce.","start":3385.923,"stop":3395.865,"duration":9.94},{"text":"For example, other types of interlocutory orders in a pending criminal proceeding.","start":3395.865,"stop":3403.741,"duration":7.88},{"text":"The State made what amounted to a type of motion to have the defendants examined set to the Tuscaloosa Hospital for mental examination to determine his present sanity or his sanity at the time of the alleged defense.","start":3403.741,"stop":3420.908,"duration":17.17},{"text":"The trial court refused to make -- to send the defendant there as a denial of certain constitutional rights which are not relevant.","start":3420.908,"stop":3431.839,"duration":10.93},{"text":"The law of Alabama is that when you have an order of that nature, fundamental to the future conduct of the proceedings that it should be tested by petition for writ of mandamus, the State in fact applied for the writ and I may also say that it's still pending, not whether the writ -- whether it's a wrong remedy, but the question of whether we're entitled of the writ, whether the order is unconstitutional.","start":3431.839,"stop":3459.907,"duration":28.07},{"text":"Now, the orderly -- this is one of these springs, these traps for the unwary that have been criticized at all.","start":3459.907,"stop":3470.502,"duration":10.59},{"text":"This is a very orderly way to proceed in these matters, every logical way to proceed in these matters, because what happens as in this case on the 11th of July, there is an order to produce at a future time.","start":3470.502,"stop":3489.522,"duration":19.02},{"text":"What is the remedy?","start":3489.522,"stop":3491.421,"duration":1.9},{"text":"File a petition for writ of mandamus in the Supreme Court of Alabama and they contest every single constitutional question concerning the justification of that order, the questions of its relevancy.","start":3491.421,"stop":3507.327,"duration":15.91},{"text":"All of those questions maybe going into, but this petitioner chose -- didn't choose that path.","start":3507.327,"stop":3514.234,"duration":6.91},{"text":"He waited until the 11th hour.","start":3514.234,"stop":3517.514,"duration":3.28},{"text":"Now, I'm a little ahead of myself.","start":3517.514,"stop":3519.538,"duration":2.02},{"text":"I should say he waited until the 23rd of July and then filed an answer.","start":3519.538,"stop":3524.943,"duration":5.41},{"text":"Now, that answer, I must disagree with counsel for the petitioner, is a rather odd type of answer and then he said, “Well, we do maintain an office and we do have a couple of employees there.","start":3524.943,"stop":3541.276,"duration":16.33},{"text":"We don't think we have to register, but we would be willing to register,” but they never really come out and say, “We're doing business in Alabama.”","start":3541.276,"stop":3552.225,"duration":10.95},{"text":"And that is an extremely important issue despite the tender of compliance with the registration statute.","start":3552.225,"stop":3560.61,"duration":8.39}]},{"speakerName":"Tom C. Clark","textObjs":[{"text":"It's more than registration of compliance by one corporation (Inaudible)","start":3560.61,"stop":3572.517,"duration":11.91}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"The statutes on that are set out in petitioner's brief at page 35.","start":3572.517,"stop":3579.417,"duration":6.9},{"text":"They are, there is more than that and of course even compliance with registration means that you have -- you can't exceed whatever powers you have.","start":3579.417,"stop":3588.272,"duration":8.86},{"text":"You can't -- you can't counter to Alabama's laws.","start":3588.272,"stop":3591.922,"duration":3.65},{"text":"All of those things involved.","start":3591.922,"stop":3593.516,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Rinehart, those statutes at 35, do I read them accurately that Section 192 requires the filing of a certified copy of articles of incorporation under seal and so forth and signed by the President and the Secretary, designating at least one known place of business and an authorized agent or agents residing thereat.","start":3593.516,"stop":3616.273,"duration":22.76},{"text":"That is within the State.","start":3616.273,"stop":3617.714,"duration":1.44},{"text":"Now, that's all wasn't it?","start":3617.714,"stop":3619.557,"duration":1.84},{"text":"Is there anything else?","start":3619.557,"stop":3620.84,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"There is a very small filing fee.","start":3620.84,"stop":3622.047,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, $10 or something like that.","start":3622.047,"stop":3624.227,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"As a matter of fact, that's one of the important questions and the reason for the relevancy of the document's requested, because the government or the theory of the State's case is not merely -- you ought to do it now, regardless of what you've done in the past and you can pay your petty little fee here and do this and go and send no more.","start":3624.227,"stop":3650.259,"duration":26.03},{"text":"We think that the State has – I didn't wish to get on this, but we think the State has a power to exclude.","start":3650.259,"stop":3657.508,"duration":7.25}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what I -- what I was interested at the moment.","start":3657.508,"stop":3660.16,"duration":2.65},{"text":"This is all that the organization was required to do to domesticate as we've been using that (Inaudible).","start":3660.16,"stop":3665.618,"duration":5.46}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"That – that is correct.","start":3665.618,"stop":3666.666,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3666.666,"stop":3666.811,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"As far as -- just coming in, if when a corporation first comes to Alabama or decides they want to, they come in and they file these papers.","start":3666.811,"stop":3674.064,"duration":7.25}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3674.064,"stop":3675.147,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that they are --","start":3675.147,"stop":3677.382,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I'm not sure, it must be true in Alabama.","start":3677.382,"stop":3679.93,"duration":2.55},{"text":"I know it is in New Jersey, but very often foreign corporations who have the same obligation in my State that they do in Europe.","start":3679.93,"stop":3687.478,"duration":7.55},{"text":"Maybe they're quite awhile before they make these filings.","start":3687.478,"stop":3690.069,"duration":2.59},{"text":"That must be so in your State, too, isn't it?","start":3690.069,"stop":3693.167,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I have no detailed information on that.","start":3693.167,"stop":3696.434,"duration":3.27},{"text":"We would take the position that they should do that before they start business.","start":3696.434,"stop":3698.633,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I know -- oh, I know.","start":3698.633,"stop":3699.81,"duration":1.18},{"text":"They take that position.","start":3699.81,"stop":3700.922,"duration":1.11},{"text":"The Secretary of State in New Jersey takes the same position, but I'm sure that there are great many of them who don't get around to doing it for some time.","start":3700.922,"stop":3707.844,"duration":6.92},{"text":"They don't all do it the first day they show up.","start":3707.844,"stop":3711.891,"duration":4.05}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I can't answer that question directly.","start":3711.891,"stop":3714.066,"duration":2.17},{"text":"I simply do not have the -- the information.","start":3714.066,"stop":3715.72,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, are you making a point of the fact that there was a delay here?","start":3715.72,"stop":3718.88,"duration":3.16}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"A -- a great delay, a many years delay.","start":3718.88,"stop":3721.453,"duration":2.57}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Whatever it was, a year or two years, whatever it maybe.","start":3721.453,"stop":3723.829,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, we are.","start":3723.829,"stop":3724.227,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You're making the point?","start":3724.227,"stop":3725.158,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, we're making that -- it's one of the most important matters in the case once we get to the question of whether the whole merits of the case are subject to review.","start":3725.158,"stop":3733.913,"duration":8.76},{"text":"Yes, we do.","start":3733.913,"stop":3741.235,"duration":7.32}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"After all, was this -- was this corporation notoriously doing business in the State?","start":3741.235,"stop":3751.323,"duration":10.09}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say, yes, sir.","start":3751.323,"stop":3752.321,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3752.321,"stop":3753.075,"duration":0.75},{"text":"And they've been notoriously doing business for a good many years.","start":3753.075,"stop":3757.12,"duration":4.05}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I can only speak of my own knowledge which would at least go back --","start":3757.12,"stop":3760.864,"duration":3.74}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no, (Voice Overlap) --","start":3760.864,"stop":3761.175,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- go back for several years, two or three years at a minimum.","start":3761.175,"stop":3766.894,"duration":5.72}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And probably before that, isn't it?","start":3766.894,"stop":3769.043,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I think in fact the petitioner admits that they have taken certain activities for great many years but denied essentially that that was doing business in Alabama.","start":3769.043,"stop":3777.048,"duration":8}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I know they do that, but I mean from the point of view of the importance to you of their disobedience from the State point of view to file a certificate or to apply for it.","start":3777.048,"stop":3787.35,"duration":10.3},{"text":"Is that right?","start":3787.35,"stop":3788.56,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3788.56,"stop":3789.233,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All I'm saying is that if they've been doing this notorious business as I should think they would take judicial notice of.","start":3789.233,"stop":3798.02,"duration":8.79},{"text":"State officials also have this knowledge and -- and therefore, it has some bearing on it on whether overnight you need to put him out of business by a restraining order.","start":3798.02,"stop":3806.753,"duration":8.73}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I think that would be correct if we ever got to the motion to dissolve the temporary restraining order, which I don't think we ever do get to really.","start":3806.753,"stop":3816.972,"duration":10.22}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Rinehart, one last question about this.","start":3816.972,"stop":3819.485,"duration":2.51},{"text":"This statute speaks of designating a known place of business and an authorized agent, authorized for what?","start":3819.485,"stop":3828.141,"duration":8.66}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Service of process.","start":3828.141,"stop":3829.357,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So that the statute has a single purpose, doesn't it, to have a place at which the officers of the State required to serve process upon it, knows where it can be reached and upon whom to make service?","start":3829.357,"stop":3842.802,"duration":13.45}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that is the most important --","start":3842.802,"stop":3845.739,"duration":2.94}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the purpose of the statute.","start":3845.739,"stop":3846.7,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the purpose of this statute.","start":3846.7,"stop":3848.317,"duration":1.62},{"text":"I should like to point out that there's a constitutional provision and it's not merely a statutory provision.","start":3848.317,"stop":3855.346,"duration":7.03},{"text":"And in fact, the constitutional provision is held to be self-enabling.","start":3855.346,"stop":3860.36,"duration":5.01},{"text":"And so, it's a question of whether you can look at this and say you have everything, though the statute doesn't say why it is.","start":3860.36,"stop":3867.967,"duration":7.61},{"text":"I mean -- I beg your pardon, the constitutional provision, Section 232 doesn't say what its purpose is except to protect people for this service or process.","start":3867.967,"stop":3877.706,"duration":9.74}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I mean there's nothing unusual about this.","start":3877.706,"stop":3879.375,"duration":1.67}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":3879.375,"stop":3879.384,"duration":0.01}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Then give me one of the 48 states has an identical statute, doesn't it?","start":3879.384,"stop":3883.004,"duration":3.62}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"There is question of franchise taxes involved also which they are supposed to, but they -- before -- to get an exemption from certain taxes, you must establish the nature of your corporation, too.","start":3883.004,"stop":3892.158,"duration":9.15},{"text":"And of course we're not making a great point of that in this particular case.","start":3892.158,"stop":3896.982,"duration":4.82},{"text":"Rather, we --","start":3896.982,"stop":3900.72,"duration":3.74}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Rinehart, if -- if a corporation is delinquent in complying with law, is there any authority of anyone in the State to prohibit them from complying with the law when they are -- was called to their attention?","start":3900.72,"stop":3919.238,"duration":18.52}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"There is no such statutory authority.","start":3919.238,"stop":3921.301,"duration":2.06}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is there any authority?","start":3921.301,"stop":3924.024,"duration":2.72},{"text":"We -- yes.","start":3924.024,"stop":3924.629,"duration":0.61},{"text":"We think -- we think the authority can be found in State ex rel Griffith against Knights and the Ku Klux Klan, a Kansas case.","start":3924.629,"stop":3932.928,"duration":8.3}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":3932.928,"stop":3933.581,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, a Kansas case?","start":3933.581,"stop":3935.098,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":3935.098,"stop":3936.732,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what I am getting at is this.","start":3936.732,"stop":3940.155,"duration":3.42},{"text":"Has it ever been declared to be the law of Alabama that anybody in the State can -- can prevent them from complying merely because they were delinquent?","start":3940.155,"stop":3953.357,"duration":13.2}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"There is no case law and no statutory law, either.","start":3953.357,"stop":3955.417,"duration":2.06}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"No case or statutory law.","start":3955.417,"stop":3957.292,"duration":1.88},{"text":"Well now, then I suppose we have to go to -- to what laws we -- we have and I notice here that -- that the -- on page 35 of the brief for our petitioner that you just called our attention to that there are certain penalties prescribed for not complying and for doing business without complying.","start":3957.292,"stop":3979.602,"duration":22.31},{"text":"If that is true and the State has set those penalties and there is no other statutory law or no -- no judicial law, aren't those the only penalties that you should be looking at exactly?","start":3979.602,"stop":3994.066,"duration":14.46}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"No --","start":3994.066,"stop":3994.265,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I think you might as well answer that in the morning.","start":3994.265,"stop":3996.653,"duration":2.39},{"text":"We'll --","start":3996.653,"stop":3996.761,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":3996.761,"stop":3997.07,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- adjourn.","start":3997.07,"stop":4001.017,"duration":3.95}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - January 16, 1958","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren6/oral_argument_audio/13442","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 91, National Association for the Advance of Colored People, Petitioner, versus State of Alabama.","start":0,"stop":9.46,"duration":9.46},{"text":"Mr. Patterson or Mr. Rinehart, I beg your pardon.","start":9.46,"stop":14.234,"duration":4.77}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, just before closing you asked me a question concerning the Alabama statutes dealing with these domestication statutes and the enforcement thereof.","start":14.234,"stop":28.49,"duration":14.26}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":28.49,"stop":30.225,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"There are two criminal statutes.","start":30.225,"stop":33.483,"duration":3.26},{"text":"They are set out in the petitioner's brief at page 36 in a footnote.","start":33.483,"stop":55.735,"duration":22.25},{"text":"They -- one of those denies a foreign corporation which makes a contract in Alabama the power to assert their rights under that contract.","start":55.735,"stop":67.234,"duration":11.5}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":67.234,"stop":69.017,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"They had also set certain penalties which are misdemeanors and those are enforced by the solicitors of our respective circuits and counties and on appeals where the Attorney General's Office would handle loss.","start":69.017,"stop":84.438,"duration":15.42},{"text":"Those are the only statutes in Alabama which deal with what we would call the enforcement, that is the method of penalizing a corporation or its agents for coming in and doing business without a license.","start":84.438,"stop":99.768,"duration":15.33},{"text":"We do not place our action or base our action in any way on those.","start":99.768,"stop":105.816,"duration":6.05},{"text":"In fact, part of the basis of our action is that those do not provide an adequate remedy at law.","start":105.816,"stop":112.855,"duration":7.04}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What I was thinking about Mr. Rinehart was whether it has a penalty for having -- having been delinquent in that query.","start":112.855,"stop":124.911,"duration":12.06},{"text":"There was any authority in anyone to say to that corporation that you cannot now qualify.","start":124.911,"stop":132.714,"duration":7.8},{"text":"I consider there will be many number of penalties that might attach to it but is there such a penalty as a denial of the right to register because of the delinquency in registering beforehand.","start":132.714,"stop":152.186,"duration":19.47}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Not a penalty but we believe a power in the court of equity in its equity jurisdiction to police, perhaps police is not the correct word, to supervise corporations once it has jurisdiction of the subject matter in this case to maintain the status quo.","start":152.186,"stop":170.428,"duration":18.24},{"text":"We petitioned not only for temporary injunction but a permanent injunction and ultimately an order of ouster basing it on the power of the state to exclude a corporation completely.","start":170.428,"stop":187.19,"duration":16.76},{"text":"If we had not in the first place let it in, we don't -- we actually concede, if we let a corporation in, we allowed to qualify, we can't then turn around and say, “We're sorry, we just don't like you anymore.”","start":187.19,"stop":199.01,"duration":11.82},{"text":"Or we can't ask them to waive their constitutional rights in advance and coming in as a condition preceding to entry.","start":199.01,"stop":205.726,"duration":6.72},{"text":"But where they are interlopers as we consider this corporation to be doing business in Alabama without even the slightest action toward complying with our laws that they are interlopers and that they have absolutely no right to be here and that the equity power is the only effective way to protect and vindicate the constitutional provision which is involved here -- the constitution that is of Alabama, Section 232.","start":205.726,"stop":237.239,"duration":31.51},{"text":"And that the equity courts have that power.","start":237.239,"stop":241.378,"duration":4.14},{"text":"And if they have the power to oust, they have the lesser concluded power to restrain their qualified as a -- in fact, that's one of the reasons we think that the records to get to the merits of this case -- no I mean the merits before the Circuit Court is so important in this case to determine whether or not they should be ousted in a proceeding of equity in the nature of (Inaudible) such as Kansas did in State ex rel Griffith against Knights of the Ku Klux Klan.","start":241.378,"stop":273.313,"duration":31.94},{"text":"That is the gravamen of the states petition, a sworn bill, I might add, a sworn bill in equity which was filed on June 1, 1956.","start":273.313,"stop":286.051,"duration":12.74}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Does your statute regarding the domestication of foreign corporation have a provision that until such a certificate of whatever you call it, have foreign corporation can sue in your court?","start":286.051,"stop":302.076,"duration":16.03}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"If they are doing business in Alabama without qualifying, they cannot sue at our courts.","start":302.076,"stop":307.694,"duration":5.62},{"text":"That is correct.","start":307.694,"stop":309.035,"duration":1.34},{"text":"I am -- I stand corrected on that.","start":309.035,"stop":310.851,"duration":1.82},{"text":"They may not enforce rights in our court growing out of that business in Alabama.","start":310.851,"stop":314.318,"duration":3.47},{"text":"Yes, a corporation may come in and sue for instance an insurance company in certain conditions and that is not considered doing business --","start":314.318,"stop":320.15,"duration":5.83}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"They are legal person capable of being brought, coming in to Court and being brought to this case shows in to Court.","start":320.15,"stop":327.284,"duration":7.13}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":327.284,"stop":328.594,"duration":1.31},{"text":"And -- if that is why (Voice Overlap) --","start":328.594,"stop":330.801,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- got a legal existence as it were subject to handicap.","start":330.801,"stop":334.482,"duration":3.68}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Of an extremely limited nature.","start":334.482,"stop":335.937,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I know but they're subject to handicaps.","start":335.937,"stop":338.257,"duration":2.32}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct, sir.","start":338.257,"stop":339.385,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not clear as to what you consider the relevance here, the records to be --","start":339.385,"stop":346.025,"duration":6.64}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Just this, our -- we allege that they are doing intrastate business in Alabama.","start":346.025,"stop":354.656,"duration":8.63},{"text":"We -- one of the most important phases of that business and there are others alleged which are not admitted is that they are soliciting members.","start":354.656,"stop":366.623,"duration":11.97},{"text":"We allege and believe a large number of members.","start":366.623,"stop":369.052,"duration":2.43},{"text":"That is a financial transaction conducted in Alabama by agents of this organization to support branches which we alleged they control on Alabama.","start":369.052,"stop":381.201,"duration":12.15},{"text":"And if that is doing business in Alabama that we are in the position of proving that and it's going -- the best way of proving how a corporation operates that I know of, is to get their records and look at them and see what they really do, what their own record show.","start":381.201,"stop":397.083,"duration":15.88}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Carter said yesterday (Inaudible)","start":397.083,"stop":403.364,"duration":6.28}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":403.364,"stop":403.693,"duration":0.33},{"text":"They we're prepared to admit and if I may, I shall read from the record.I am now reading from record pages 6 and 7, the last full paragraph on page 6 beginning on July 23.","start":403.693,"stop":433.18,"duration":29.49},{"text":"Petitioner filed his answer admitting (1) that it was a New York corporation, (2) that it maintains its southeast regional office in Birmingham, (3) that it hired employee agents to operate this office but denied that he did organized local chapters in the state and that the agents of the corporation's solicited for said local chapters and apparent corporation, denied that he did employ or paid money to Autherine Lucy and Pollie Myers Hudson to encourage or aid them enrolling in the University of Alabama.","start":433.18,"stop":463.82,"duration":30.64},{"text":"Admitted six, furnishing legal counsel to Autherine Lucy in prosecuting her suit against the University of Alabama.","start":463.82,"stop":471.388,"duration":7.57},{"text":"Admitted seven, it had given moral and financial support to Negro residents of Montgomery in connection with their refusal to use the public transportation system of Montgomery and had furnished legal counsel to assist (Inaudible) M. L. King and other Negros indicted in connection with that matter.","start":471.388,"stop":489.937,"duration":18.55},{"text":"But denied all other allegations and inferences contained in that allegation in bill of complaint and denied eight that its officers, agents or employees have engaged in organizing chapters for the corporation in Alabama and Montgomery County, collecting dues, soliciting memberships, loaning or giving personal property to aid present aim to the corporation, admitted that it had never filed with the Secretary of State, Articles of Incorporation or designated place of business or authorized agents within the state but denied ten, that it was required by Sections192, 193 and 194 of Title 10, Code of Alabama in 1940 to do so.","start":489.937,"stop":531.848,"duration":41.91},{"text":"Petitioner denied that it has violated Article XII, Section 232, Constitution of Alabama 1901 and Section 192, 193 and 194, Title 10, Code of Alabama 1940.","start":531.848,"stop":545.151,"duration":13.3},{"text":"Further, petitioner denied 11 that these acts are causing irreparable injury to the property of civil rights of the citizens, residents and citizens of the State of Alabama.","start":545.151,"stop":555.308,"duration":10.16},{"text":"Now, we do not concede that that is an admission of doing business in Alabama.In fact, it is one of those things to say we're admitting we're doing A, B and C but we deny these other things and when you get all finished, your laws don't apply.","start":555.308,"stop":572.177,"duration":16.87},{"text":"Now Section 232 was all inclusive, it says all corporations doing business in Alabama, and I could only construe that to mean that they're are saying that “While we admit doing certain things, we're not doing business in Alabama within the meaning of your laws.”","start":572.177,"stop":586.702,"duration":14.52}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Rinehart, doesn't next paragraph though bear on that?","start":586.702,"stop":597.645,"duration":10.94}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean the assertion that --","start":597.645,"stop":599.602,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a short paragraph, I suppose you read that.","start":599.602,"stop":602.546,"duration":2.94}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":602.546,"stop":604.009,"duration":1.46},{"text":"In addition to the various defenses to the bill of complaint, petitioner, while asserting the Title 10, Sections 192, 193 and 194 of the Code of Alabama 1940 was not applicable, had procured the necessary forms from the Office of the Secretary of State, Montgomery, Alabama and had filled in the forms as required by law and offered to file the same.","start":604.009,"stop":627.164,"duration":23.15},{"text":"Said forms were attached to his answer and petitioner stated that it would file these forms if the court would dissolve its orders buying petition from registering and would permit petitioner to file the forms attached to his answer.","start":627.164,"stop":642.053,"duration":14.89},{"text":"We submit it does not and for some very definite reasons.","start":642.053,"stop":648.668,"duration":6.62},{"text":"One, on reviewing the chronology of this case, you will see that petitioner didn't file any pleadings until 31 days after the temporary injunction of that, on the fifth of July which was three days after and I might add, that then the trial judge set down the hearing on a motion to dissolve a temporary injunction for the 16th of July.","start":648.668,"stop":674.734,"duration":26.07},{"text":"The State then moved to produce -- rather moved for an order for them to produce, which motion was heard on the 9th of July which counsel for the petitioner was present.","start":674.734,"stop":687.552,"duration":12.82},{"text":"The case was fully argued and presented on that question purely of the production and the order was granted on the 11th.","start":687.552,"stop":697.762,"duration":10.21},{"text":"Then their time was extended.","start":697.762,"stop":702.66,"duration":4.9},{"text":"Then the order said produce on the 16th which was the day before the hearing on the motion to dissolve the temporary injunction.","start":702.66,"stop":712.004,"duration":9.34},{"text":"Now, Alabama procedure is that while oral testimony may not be introduced on such a hearing as a matter of right, you can put it in if it isn't objected to.","start":712.004,"stop":722.662,"duration":10.66},{"text":"But in addition, the hearing can be on affidavits of both sides.","start":722.662,"stop":727.852,"duration":5.19},{"text":"We thought it's extremely important to have those records to sustain and (Inaudible) the allegations of the bill to prepare affidavits, to obtain affidavits.","start":727.852,"stop":739.804,"duration":11.95},{"text":"Then the trial judge extended their time to produce.He correspondingly extended our time for the hearing because we needed those documents in connection with the hearing.","start":739.804,"stop":750.211,"duration":10.41},{"text":"Now then, at the last hour or if not the 12th hour, at least the 11th hour, they come in with an answer.","start":750.211,"stop":759.109,"duration":8.9},{"text":"Now, we're not interested in a corporation filing these papers if they don't have to file them.If they are exempt, they don't need to tender it.","start":759.109,"stop":769.153,"duration":10.04},{"text":"Alabama isn't interested in a corporation not doing business in Alabama, filing these documents.","start":769.153,"stop":774.664,"duration":5.51},{"text":"We are not trying to assert a right we don't have but we think we're entitled to a hearing on the merits as to whether or not they are doing business in Alabama because our ultimate aim in this, admittedly, I couldn't deny it on what we've alleged here, is that we think they are long-past record of ignoring our laws warranted something more than a slap on the wrist saying, “Well, now you can pay it and go and send no more.”","start":774.664,"stop":805.583,"duration":30.92},{"text":"But we felt that like Kansas, we had a right to oust them, completely.","start":805.583,"stop":809.669,"duration":4.09}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask you this.","start":809.669,"stop":812.219,"duration":2.55},{"text":"You correct me if I misunderstand it -- if my understanding is inaccurate.","start":812.219,"stop":819.47,"duration":7.25},{"text":"You brought out the proceeding against the NAACP.","start":819.47,"stop":824.368,"duration":4.9},{"text":"They said they didn't come within your law either because they are a membership corporation of New York or because what they did in Alabama does not include what legally speaking is doing business in Alabama.","start":824.368,"stop":837.622,"duration":13.25},{"text":"But they said as you can have them to say, I think to seldom say on the advice of counsel, well whether we are right or wrong and lead him first to comply.","start":837.622,"stop":850.609,"duration":12.99},{"text":"So they say we're ready to file this certificate if this is what you want.","start":850.609,"stop":854.857,"duration":4.25},{"text":"But they did contend the coercive power of Alabama to make this file.","start":854.857,"stop":860.279,"duration":5.42},{"text":"That's correct isn't it?","start":860.279,"stop":863.782,"duration":3.5},{"text":"Didn't they deny that they come within your law requiring to do anything including what they did do in Alabama?","start":863.782,"stop":871.523,"duration":7.74}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I agree what they offered to do in Alabama.","start":871.523,"stop":874.907,"duration":3.38}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what they -- but you said, they have been doing over these years during which they didn't file -- that they should have filed a certificate and domesticate themselves, isn't that true?","start":874.907,"stop":884.027,"duration":9.12},{"text":"You said they've been doing business for good many years in Alabama and certainly way back since 1918 or probably earlier in connection with their purposes.","start":884.027,"stop":891.806,"duration":7.78}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":891.806,"stop":892.698,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So that you say, you've been doing business without the requisite provision of Alabama.","start":892.698,"stop":899.423,"duration":6.73},{"text":"They said, “We don't come within your law.We didn't have to satisfy the requirements of getting a certificate but in the interest of whatever it is, convenience, we are ready to file this certificate.”","start":899.423,"stop":911.646,"duration":12.22},{"text":"And you said, “No, we don't have to accept it.”","start":911.646,"stop":913.616,"duration":1.97},{"text":"Is that right?","start":913.616,"stop":914.212,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":914.212,"stop":915.343,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, and on the basis of the facts that's quickly summarized, the State got a restraining order against them calling for the cessation of all business although they raised, what I supposed, is not a frivolous or a ridiculous objection to the claim asserted by the State.","start":915.343,"stop":936.726,"duration":21.38},{"text":"Is that right?","start":936.726,"stop":938.633,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I --","start":938.633,"stop":938.687,"duration":0.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I know you don't -- you don't think there's much to the point, but sometimes it drives how often -- a majority of my brothers think there's something to a point which I think there's nothing or by subversive.","start":938.687,"stop":947.382,"duration":8.69},{"text":"[Laughter]","start":947.382,"stop":949.698,"duration":2.32}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I accept everything except the very last statement with a reservation as being absolutely a correct statement.","start":949.698,"stop":960.618,"duration":10.92}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Then correct me.","start":960.618,"stop":961.68,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":961.68,"stop":965.187,"duration":3.51},{"text":"What we say is this, first statement I will make is that the offer which they made was after the ex -- and I admit ex parte restraining order and the offer wasn't made until after we we're going to get down to the nub of the case, the facts of the case and that is something I think that should be borne in mind into spelling this which I think petitioner is trying to create, this aura of unfairness in Alabama.","start":965.187,"stop":992.901,"duration":27.71}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":992.901,"stop":993.439,"duration":0.54},{"text":"What I've stated was merely preliminary to the (Voice Overlap) --","start":993.439,"stop":995.64,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh I'm -- I'm sorry.","start":995.64,"stop":996.711,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I didn't think on that statement that Alabama did something that was wrong.","start":996.711,"stop":1001.599,"duration":4.89},{"text":"This is merely -- I want to see if the preliminary facts seemed to me irrelevant to the question I'm going to put to you or correct.","start":1001.599,"stop":1008.117,"duration":6.52}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"They are, sir.","start":1008.117,"stop":1008.969,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Very well.","start":1008.969,"stop":1010.291,"duration":1.32},{"text":"Then you get a restraining order against him not to do business.","start":1010.291,"stop":1014.118,"duration":3.83},{"text":"They must shut up sharp, is that right?","start":1014.118,"stop":1015.565,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1015.565,"stop":1016.408,"duration":0.84},{"text":"They have not at that point, however, made any offer of compliance, whatsoever.","start":1016.408,"stop":1019.863,"duration":3.46}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but you did -- you told them they must shut up sharp.","start":1019.863,"stop":1022.874,"duration":3.01}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":1022.874,"stop":1024.942,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Before the validity of that order, not only the validity of the order but the scope of the decree could be contested.","start":1024.942,"stop":1034.869,"duration":9.93},{"text":"The state begins another proceeding and says, produce certain documents.","start":1034.869,"stop":1039.02,"duration":4.15},{"text":"That's true, isn't it?","start":1039.02,"stop":1039.844,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":1039.844,"stop":1041.291,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"They say you are asking us to produce documents which we are entitled.","start":1041.291,"stop":1045.973,"duration":4.68},{"text":"Now whatever rights -- by the rights we have under the United States constitution to withhold.","start":1045.973,"stop":1053.299,"duration":7.33},{"text":"That certainty is not a frivolous question --","start":1053.299,"stop":1055.563,"duration":2.26}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"No, that is not a frivolous question.","start":1055.563,"stop":1057.89,"duration":2.33}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That being so, what I want to put to you is that pending the determination of what is not a frivolous question, what is a substantial question that respectable lawyers can raise and do raise and have raised, Alabama takes the position that although this organization has been in Alabama all these years without any attention or objection from the authority with Alabama.","start":1057.89,"stop":1084.462,"duration":26.57},{"text":"I am not talking about a stopple.","start":1084.462,"stop":1086.266,"duration":1.8},{"text":"I'm addressing myself to the nature of the remedy.","start":1086.266,"stop":1089.111,"duration":2.85},{"text":"Although that has been so and although they raised that question ancillary to the proceedings of oust.","start":1089.111,"stop":1097.028,"duration":7.92},{"text":"Alabama says, “You go out of business until this long trail of litigation because you have, standing on constitutional right said, “You don't have to obey this.”","start":1097.028,"stop":1110.861,"duration":13.83},{"text":"Alabama then throws them in contempt but all this time they are executed.","start":1110.861,"stop":1117.045,"duration":6.18},{"text":"They get a death sentence pro tem although in the end, it may turn out that they we're constitutionally right.","start":1117.045,"stop":1123.552,"duration":6.51},{"text":"You're not (Voice Overlap) of this litigation?","start":1123.552,"stop":1125.705,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I am going to make one correction and I think --","start":1125.705,"stop":1128.079,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Please do.","start":1128.079,"stop":1128.719,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the most important correction.","start":1128.719,"stop":1130.245,"duration":1.53},{"text":"Alabama did not throw them into contempt.","start":1130.245,"stop":1134.118,"duration":3.87},{"text":"They need never have been in contempt.","start":1134.118,"stop":1137.443,"duration":3.33},{"text":"They could have tested the order to produce without ever the slightest risk of contempt.","start":1137.443,"stop":1142.435,"duration":4.99}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well they tested it in way in which they thought they contested according to your cases.","start":1142.435,"stop":1148.249,"duration":5.81}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Our cases don't hold that in a proper way.","start":1148.249,"stop":1150.002,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But that is the question before us whether they raise it by a -- whether a certiorari by which they sought to raise it, raised all these issues.","start":1150.002,"stop":1159.816,"duration":9.81},{"text":"And even your Supreme Court said we don't have to consider this but we do consider them.","start":1159.816,"stop":1164.48,"duration":4.66},{"text":"It's the love of the counsel that they had a right to pursue (Inaudible) --","start":1164.48,"stop":1169.895,"duration":5.41}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I would like to address myself to that specific question in -- in considerable detail and explain the fairness of the Alabama procedure and that is this, the Alabama procedure on a subpoena duces tecum if in case of a third party or an order to produce documents is that that is an interlocutory order not appealable.","start":1169.895,"stop":1197.043,"duration":27.15},{"text":"The proper remedy is petition for writ of mandamus.","start":1197.043,"stop":1201.309,"duration":4.27},{"text":"And why is that?","start":1201.309,"stop":1203.269,"duration":1.96},{"text":"Because the person does not have to set himself up as the sole judge of relevancy, the sole judge of constitutionality and bring himself to the position of flat out as this petitioner did in open court and saying, “We don't need anymore time.","start":1203.269,"stop":1223.453,"duration":20.18},{"text":"We choose to stand on these rights.”","start":1223.453,"stop":1225.762,"duration":2.31}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, so far as I'm concerned, and that's the only person to whom I can ever (Inaudible).","start":1225.762,"stop":1230.12,"duration":4.36},{"text":"So far as I'm concerned, if it can be established that the orderly, traditional, settled procedure of Alabama requires the rating of these questions solely by mandamus and I think the other side is out of court so far as I'm concerned because Alabama has the right to say, “It should be raised by mandamus and not by certiorari, if you're right.","start":1230.12,"stop":1256.833,"duration":26.71}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"If I'm right.","start":1256.833,"stop":1257.528,"duration":0.69},{"text":"Well, we have cited in our brief at pages 9 and 17, thereof, Ex parte Monroe County Bank, 254 Ala. 515.","start":1257.528,"stop":1277.999,"duration":20.47},{"text":"Now that I will grant you the Monroe County Bank was not a party to the action.","start":1277.999,"stop":1283.347,"duration":5.35},{"text":"They were -- this was a subpoena duces tecum.","start":1283.347,"stop":1289.175,"duration":5.83},{"text":"In that case, they didn't choose or felt that they did not have the duty to produce certain records in a divorce proceeding.","start":1289.175,"stop":1300.693,"duration":11.52},{"text":"Husband against wife and of course these financial matters become very important.","start":1300.693,"stop":1305.878,"duration":5.18},{"text":"If they proceeded by writ of mandamus to test the validity of that subpoena duces tecum in the Alabama court and it went to the Supreme Court and all the questions we're passed on it.","start":1305.878,"stop":1320.787,"duration":14.91},{"text":"Now that isn't enough.","start":1320.787,"stop":1323.613,"duration":2.83},{"text":"That doesn't make a great long line of cases.","start":1323.613,"stop":1327.431,"duration":3.82},{"text":"In addition, Ex parte Hart cited in the Supreme Courts' opinion had a similar question of an order to produce.","start":1327.431,"stop":1337.216,"duration":9.78},{"text":"The court didn't discuss that thing at length.","start":1337.216,"stop":1340.794,"duration":3.58},{"text":"It was just the well accepted method in Alabama.","start":1340.794,"stop":1345.794,"duration":5}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If I -- if my reading with all the consciousness that one should have about reading the decisions of a state or the law which he isn't familiar except by reading.","start":1345.794,"stop":1356.529,"duration":10.73},{"text":"If my reading of your cases were a consistent document that mandamus is the crucial remedy, I would have to go with you.","start":1356.529,"stop":1365.312,"duration":8.78},{"text":"But if my reading of your cases is this that sometimes Alabama does and sometimes Alabama doesn't allow all the substantive questions to be raised on certiorari then I'd say to you that it can't invoke that doctrine when the federal right is asserted when it doesn't invoke at another instances.","start":1365.312,"stop":1381.58,"duration":16.27}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":1381.58,"stop":1382.837,"duration":1.26},{"text":"I -- I don't know of a case where a petition for certiorari has ever been treated as a petition for writ of mandamus.","start":1382.837,"stop":1390.86,"duration":8.02}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That is what I suggested.","start":1390.86,"stop":1392.454,"duration":1.59},{"text":"I don't think this Court -- I don't think I can say that that which the Supreme Court of Alabama treats a certiorari should be deemed to be a mandamus.","start":1392.454,"stop":1400.072,"duration":7.62},{"text":"That's not my function.","start":1400.072,"stop":1401.661,"duration":1.59},{"text":"But if I find that on certiorari, it has intermittently considered all substantive questions and then it can draw the curtain when a federal question is (Inaudible).","start":1401.661,"stop":1412.218,"duration":10.56}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"The cases which both parties have cited, Ex parte Morris at pages 8, 14 and 15 of the respondent's brief, is a case which comes to mind as well as the instant case.","start":1412.218,"stop":1430.87,"duration":18.65},{"text":"Of course we submit in the instant case the Supreme Court of Alabama said we are going to exposit essentially.","start":1430.87,"stop":1437.704,"duration":6.83},{"text":"We're going to demonstrate for future guidance of use but they did not make them the basis of the decision.","start":1437.704,"stop":1443.932,"duration":6.23},{"text":"And I think that's a very important distinction to make and extremely important one in this case and also in Ex parte Morris.","start":1443.932,"stop":1451.225,"duration":7.29},{"text":"Ex parte Morris concerned this question.","start":1451.225,"stop":1456.979,"duration":5.75},{"text":"A -- an officer of the Ku Klux Klan was directed to bring before the grand jury records of that corporation -- of that organization.","start":1456.979,"stop":1469.855,"duration":12.88}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Is this the Kansas case you're --","start":1469.855,"stop":1471.802,"duration":1.95}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"No, this is not, sir.","start":1471.802,"stop":1472.711,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"This is was in Alabama --","start":1472.711,"stop":1473.217,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"This is an Alabama case.","start":1473.217,"stop":1474.357,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1474.357,"stop":1475.942,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"This was a grand jury proceeding on a preliminary I suppose to some criminal action.","start":1475.942,"stop":1479.991,"duration":4.05}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1479.991,"stop":1481.058,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"And he said he stood on his constitutional rights not to do it and was held in contempt.","start":1481.058,"stop":1490.605,"duration":9.55},{"text":"He -- he was brought in before the judge and the judge says, “You'll produce them.”","start":1490.605,"stop":1495.102,"duration":4.5},{"text":"Now, he then filed a petition for certiorari which is the established law of Alabama for reviewing contempt citations whether civil or criminal and a writ for certiorari was denied because on the face of the proceedings, the Court had jurisdiction, nice little memorandum decision.","start":1495.102,"stop":1521.553,"duration":26.45},{"text":"Then they said, “However, we're going to exposit our views on these constitutional questions, not as a basis of decision as I read the case.","start":1521.553,"stop":1530.052,"duration":8.5},{"text":"But merely because we'd like people to know that corporations, for example, don't have a privilege against self-incrimination, don't have a right of secrecy.”","start":1530.052,"stop":1538.898,"duration":8.85},{"text":"Now those are the chief cases which I have studied on this other than -- and that I know of myself that really face up to these problems except Ex parte Dickens also cited in petitioner's brief and our brief.","start":1538.898,"stop":1553.163,"duration":14.27},{"text":"If you wish, I will refer the page number and I think I can explain that case too, and it shows that the merits of the case we're not considered.","start":1553.163,"stop":1565.214,"duration":12.05},{"text":"In that case, petition for certiorari, what was considered was contempt of an order to deliver certain bonds and other documents to a receiver and equity.","start":1565.214,"stop":1586.01,"duration":20.8},{"text":"The Court reiterated the traditional view that certiorari -- you look at the face of the proceedings.","start":1586.01,"stop":1593.846,"duration":7.84},{"text":"You see whether there was jurisdiction of the persons -- the parties I should say, jurisdiction of the subject matter, whether there was a contempt, whether all the procedural aspects of a contempt proceeding are followed, remembering that it is a completely ancillary proceeding.","start":1593.846,"stop":1610.701,"duration":16.86},{"text":"Now, and they held that in fact since the face of the proceeding is so that in fact the he had obeyed the order and that there hadn't been any new order, even though a new receiver had been appointed, there was no contempt.","start":1610.701,"stop":1625.604,"duration":14.9},{"text":"They went on to say that if there was a question of a payment of a debt, the debt could be reviewed on petition for writ of habeas corpus.","start":1625.604,"stop":1637.497,"duration":11.89},{"text":"Now they didn't say -- they didn't do as the Morris case and in this case.","start":1637.497,"stop":1640.807,"duration":3.31},{"text":"They didn't say, “Well, now, we said all, we're got to say all we have to say.”","start":1640.807,"stop":1647.044,"duration":6.24},{"text":"They just went on and discussed this question of writ of habeas corpus that had he been imprisoned in this case to pay a debt which might well had been the case, why then he could have reviewed it for petition for writ of habeas corpus.","start":1647.044,"stop":1659.763,"duration":12.72},{"text":"Now, there maybe other cases in Alabama, I regret I don't know of any other which bears on this issue.","start":1659.763,"stop":1669.927,"duration":10.16}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Now suppose -- suppose one finds that while, as a matter of (Inaudible), your court thinks mandamus is the way to do it but suppose as a matter of practice, one finds that in fact they do consider, in fact, as a matter of judicial habit or course of judicial practice.","start":1669.927,"stop":1693.943,"duration":24.02},{"text":"They do consider the merit and that one further finds that they've been drawn -- they drew the distinction in this case but they haven't gone with others and reaches the merits.","start":1693.943,"stop":1703.689,"duration":9.75},{"text":"Let's make that assumption --","start":1703.689,"stop":1704.729,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand it --","start":1704.729,"stop":1705.271,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"-- if you can.","start":1705.271,"stop":1706.542,"duration":1.27},{"text":"We lawyers can see both sides as we are supposed to.","start":1706.542,"stop":1710.062,"duration":3.52},{"text":"Why do you say then assuming that the case is here in other words is not to be dismissed because, one, of the federal question and the other one of the disposition of a -- in a local ground, what do you say to the procedure, to the decree of the restraining order which puts and an enterprise out of business although it raises -- barely raises federal constitutional question and although no -- no grounds at least I heard, mentioned, given some.","start":1710.062,"stop":1744.211,"duration":34.15},{"text":"There's no -- no serious ground for saying anything will happen.","start":1744.211,"stop":1748.648,"duration":4.44},{"text":"There will be irreparable damage if you, for the time being, you don't put a body out of business although ultimately it maybe found that you had no business to restrain it all.","start":1748.648,"stop":1766.552,"duration":17.9}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I am to assume this fact and this is the only one I understand that the case history of Alabama shows that while they pretend to this nicety of pleading in practice, that in fact when they get one of these important questions where they simply just say, “Well, we're going to look at the thing anyway.”","start":1766.552,"stop":1788.946,"duration":22.39},{"text":"That's -- that's what I am to assume.","start":1788.946,"stop":1792.425,"duration":3.48}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And -- and that -- that they drew the line here that you're asking us to draw the line here but we find the case that as a matter of fact your court did review it -- did review the issues, the federal question that it is here that is sought to be brought here and that therefore it is just (Voice Overlap) --","start":1792.425,"stop":1813.943,"duration":21.52}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Then I think that there is -- that the State of Alabama has -- has an extremely dubious case of no federal question.","start":1813.943,"stop":1823.823,"duration":9.88},{"text":"In other words, that -- that -- but if you can reach this position which I would -- it would seem to me you were heading that they decided to make some sort of an exception in this case.","start":1823.823,"stop":1837.413,"duration":13.59},{"text":"Then it -- I think it were perilously close to a case which was decided here Monday, this Baxley case.","start":1837.413,"stop":1849.24,"duration":11.83}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. --","start":1849.24,"stop":1850.482,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't concede entrapment however or springs in this case.","start":1850.482,"stop":1854.607,"duration":4.13}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Rinehart, how in Alabama do you raise the question of whether or not a preliminary injunction was legally or illegally entered?","start":1854.607,"stop":1874.494,"duration":19.89}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"On a motion to dissolve.","start":1874.494,"stop":1875.929,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's what I thought.","start":1875.929,"stop":1877.138,"duration":1.21},{"text":"Now, until the motion to resolve has been heard, you have -- you're not out of the trial court and there is nothing yet to review.","start":1877.138,"stop":1889.511,"duration":12.37}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"That is our contention and that is correct under my understanding of the law.","start":1889.511,"stop":1893.655,"duration":4.14}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, you have two aspects here, one is the temporary injunction but as a collateral appendix to the determination of the question of whether or not the injunction might be maintained.","start":1893.655,"stop":1910.986,"duration":17.33},{"text":"An argument was entered by the trial court for the production of certain documents.","start":1910.986,"stop":1918.04,"duration":7.05}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":1918.04,"stop":1920.235,"duration":2.19}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Under the law of Alabama, does the court have an inherent or a statutory power to impose penalty for disobedience of his order?","start":1920.235,"stop":1931.551,"duration":11.32}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"It has an inherent power.","start":1931.551,"stop":1933.376,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":1933.376,"stop":1933.84,"duration":0.46},{"text":"Now --","start":1933.84,"stop":1934.67,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"And also a statutory in the case of criminal contempt.","start":1934.67,"stop":1937.449,"duration":2.78}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, what's the remedy -- that's final when the penalty is assessed, isn't it?","start":1937.449,"stop":1945.648,"duration":8.2},{"text":"That's -- that's immediately reviewable whether by appeal, certiorari, mandamus or whatnot, isn't it?","start":1945.648,"stop":1951.202,"duration":5.55}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":1951.202,"stop":1952.3,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, how do you get a review on that issue, you say by mandamus, is that right?","start":1952.3,"stop":1963.406,"duration":11.11}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Because we break it down into -- into two steps, you have really two ancillary proceedings and ancillary questions.","start":1963.406,"stop":1969.181,"duration":5.78},{"text":"You have first the validity of the order to produce which is tested by mandamus and secondly, then if they choose to just say as this petitioner did, we're not going to -- we ignore I don't know why they didn't file a petition for writ of mandamus but they did to test only the order to produce and if you then choose the route of saying --","start":1969.181,"stop":1992.686,"duration":23.5}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, to test only the conviction for contempt for disobedience to the order to produce, that's what you mean isn't it?","start":1992.686,"stop":2000.702,"duration":8.02}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2000.702,"stop":2001.038,"duration":0.34},{"text":"First, the mandamus goes only to test the validity of the order to produce and maybe commenced anytime after the order is entered and being an interlocutory non-appealable order.","start":2001.038,"stop":2011.814,"duration":10.78}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Now in Missouri, you would have to do this not by mandamus but by a prohibition.","start":2011.814,"stop":2017.417,"duration":5.6},{"text":"Now, but in your state, you do it by mandamus.","start":2017.417,"stop":2020.429,"duration":3.01}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Frankly, if I may say so, the writ of mandamus and writ of prohibition are -- are -- if I were a purist, I would say often what appears to be mandamus is a writ of prohibition.","start":2020.429,"stop":2030.777,"duration":10.35}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Now let's go back to the injunction feature, the temporary injunction.How is that reviewed after the motion for -- to dissolve has been overruled?","start":2030.777,"stop":2041.972,"duration":11.19},{"text":"How do you review that?","start":2041.972,"stop":2043.808,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"By appeal.","start":2043.808,"stop":2044.593,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"By a direct appeal.","start":2044.593,"stop":2045.84,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":2045.84,"stop":2048.996,"duration":3.16}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Is the certiorari -- one more question.","start":2048.996,"stop":2051.735,"duration":2.74},{"text":"Is certiorari a discretionary writ in Alabama?","start":2051.735,"stop":2055.731,"duration":4}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Absolutely and there is a very important point to me in connection with that.","start":2055.731,"stop":2060.127,"duration":4.4},{"text":"Mr. Justice Brennan.","start":2060.127,"stop":2060.453,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I just want to be sure I understand this..","start":2060.453,"stop":2063.625,"duration":3.17},{"text":"Are you suggesting that on your analysis of the Alabama cases, there is none where in fact in review on certiorari of an order of civil contempt, your Supreme Court has ever reviewed the merits of an order of the underlying order which -- which was disobeyed and upon which the contempt finding was made?","start":2063.625,"stop":2089.223,"duration":25.6}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":2089.223,"stop":2090.934,"duration":1.71},{"text":"Now, there was a case cited yesterday which I was not personally aware of.","start":2090.934,"stop":2098.531,"duration":7.6},{"text":"I believe I have that citation 68 So.2d 834, this Armstrong case which is a -- we maintained -- the Court did not look at the merits.","start":2098.531,"stop":2115.002,"duration":16.47},{"text":"This is one of those cases where they applied for certiorari and it was treated as mandamus.","start":2115.002,"stop":2119.755,"duration":4.75},{"text":"The case isn't at all that case.","start":2119.755,"stop":2122.098,"duration":2.34}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I'm not addressing myself to that.","start":2122.098,"stop":2124.317,"duration":2.22},{"text":"I'm addressing myself to what happens when in fact an order of civil contempt is reviewed on writ of certiorari --","start":2124.317,"stop":2132.66,"duration":8.34}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh this was --","start":2132.66,"stop":2133.032,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Does your Supreme Court entertain argument and dispose of any arguments addressed to the validity of the order allege to have been disobeyed.","start":2133.032,"stop":2147.394,"duration":14.36}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"At Armstrong case, it's the only case that I know of that bears -- that seems to even bear on it.","start":2147.394,"stop":2156.308,"duration":8.91},{"text":"And that in fact was an appeal from the denial of the Court to hold the man in contempt to take contempt proceeding against and even though he had very possibly on a record violated the order and then they threw in a sort of general prayer on top of the appeal.","start":2156.308,"stop":2183.172,"duration":26.86},{"text":"And the Court reviewed the portion of the contempt proceedings, they also reviewed other matters on the merits of the whole case as I see it on the appeal feature but specifically on the contempt feature, they said, “Well, as far as this contempt -- pure contempt angle, we will consider to that extent certiorari,” and they did in fact.","start":2183.172,"stop":2204.952,"duration":21.78},{"text":"They didn't look at the merits except to this extent which is the established Alabama law to see whether or not there was a contempt.","start":2204.952,"stop":2215.164,"duration":10.21}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, did that involve -- whether or not there was a contempt that is whether or not there was disobedience for the order?","start":2215.164,"stop":2221.045,"duration":5.88}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":2221.045,"stop":2221.912,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And to decide whether there's been a disobedience to the order, don't perhaps decide whether the features of the order alleged to have been disobeyed or valid or not?","start":2221.912,"stop":2235.976,"duration":14.06}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I see what you're -- absolutely what you're getting at.","start":2235.976,"stop":2239.96,"duration":3.98}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm just --","start":2239.96,"stop":2240.729,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I understand.","start":2240.729,"stop":2241.775,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The scope of the actual review on certiorari and a civil contempt proceeding.","start":2241.775,"stop":2254.894,"duration":13.12}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"In that case, they did in fact told that this was a proper order and as I say, it seem to me they looked at it on the appeal feature.","start":2254.894,"stop":2264.129,"duration":9.24},{"text":"In other words they appealed -- in this question of appeal whether the order was an order which was proper.","start":2264.129,"stop":2272.09,"duration":7.96},{"text":"They didn't --","start":2272.09,"stop":2272.858,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"In relation to the injunction feature?","start":2272.858,"stop":2275.128,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, not in our case.","start":2275.128,"stop":2276.185,"duration":1.06},{"text":"I'm not speaking of that, Mr. Justice Whittaker.","start":2276.185,"stop":2278.491,"duration":2.31},{"text":"I'm taking about this Armstrong case which was a -- one of this custody of children cases among other things and also a question of accrued alimony.","start":2278.491,"stop":2288.854,"duration":10.36},{"text":"There are a number of complicating features.","start":2288.854,"stop":2293.121,"duration":4.27},{"text":"I -- I see the -- not only the drift of the question but you do get sort to that point and all I can say is that as far as the way the Court talks they say we're looking strictly at the face of these contempt proceedings for jurisdiction.","start":2293.121,"stop":2310.968,"duration":17.85}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well what -- what I'm getting at is -- anyone reading the Alabama cases and finding that in fact on a writ of certiorari, the review of civil contempt order that the Supreme Court of Alabama actually inquires into the validity of the order alleged to have been disobeyed.","start":2310.968,"stop":2336.633,"duration":25.66},{"text":"Will he not think that that was an appropriate -- he might appropriately believe that the next time he came up by certiorari not only with the contempt itself whether there's been a disobedience but as well whether or not what was disobeyed was valid would be considered by your Supreme Court.","start":2336.633,"stop":2357.504,"duration":20.87}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that if the case is in fact ran that way I think that you would be correct.","start":2357.504,"stop":2363.944,"duration":6.44},{"text":"I -- I don't know that -- I don't know of any cases that do go that way.","start":2363.944,"stop":2368.31,"duration":4.37},{"text":"The Armstrong case has opposed this thing to that.","start":2368.31,"stop":2370.668,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Frankly, what I'm addressing myself to, I notice that you have -- your Supreme Court had a per curiam which is in 91 So. 2d 221.","start":2370.668,"stop":2384.397,"duration":13.73},{"text":"At the time there was an application for stay in the Supreme Court, I think that was the application of July 31st, wasn't it?","start":2384.397,"stop":2392.404,"duration":8.01}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I would likely to explain exactly what happened in that case.","start":2392.404,"stop":2396.681,"duration":4.28},{"text":"They made an application for stay.","start":2396.681,"stop":2398.055,"duration":1.37},{"text":"There's no petition for certiorari or with any kind of pleading.","start":2398.055,"stop":2400.417,"duration":2.36},{"text":"They just went up there and said --","start":2400.417,"stop":2401.379,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2401.379,"stop":2401.39,"duration":0.01}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"“We're in this terrible fix.","start":2401.39,"stop":2402.421,"duration":1.03},{"text":"There were no facts or anything, just stay in the proceedings.”","start":2402.421,"stop":2405.421,"duration":3},{"text":"And the court said, “We -- when there -- it's a question of a contempt proceeding certiorari -- the contempt proceeding, the review of a contempt proceeding, we have to have a petition for certiorari.”","start":2405.421,"stop":2415.33,"duration":9.91},{"text":"(Voice Overlap) jurisdiction.","start":2415.33,"stop":2416.231,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's just the point but the way the per curiam reads this, it is the established rule of this Court that the proper method of reviewing a judgment for civil contempt to the kind here involved is by a petition for common law writ of certiorari.","start":2416.231,"stop":2430.664,"duration":14.43},{"text":"And this Court as through the years upheld to grant the writ for the purposes of review where a reasonable ground for its issuance is properly presented in such petition.","start":2430.664,"stop":2439.889,"duration":9.22},{"text":"And it was after that decision and that per curiam that the first petition for certiorari, I see it's all on the same page, on August 13 rather cryptically was denied on the ground that the insufficient to warrant the issuance of the writ, the averments of the petitioner insufficient as to say in what respect insufficient.","start":2439.889,"stop":2465.083,"duration":25.19},{"text":"And then it was followed on August, the petition which led to the judgment and opinion before us and I'm just was wondering how anyone was involved in this very case.","start":2465.083,"stop":2477.315,"duration":12.23},{"text":"If reading your cases before this one felt that there was going to be a review both of the underlying order as well as of the contempt itself.","start":2477.315,"stop":2490.397,"duration":13.08},{"text":"I could help but take this as an instruction of your Supreme Court, go ahead and follow the root of writ of certiorari and we will consider both the contempt and the order upon which it would take.","start":2490.397,"stop":2501.688,"duration":11.29}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"First of all, taking what was actually before the Court in the second petition, it amount -- it had no facts alleged.","start":2501.688,"stop":2513.624,"duration":11.94},{"text":"They were merely what we can call assignments of error which are set out in our briefs.","start":2513.624,"stop":2529.665,"duration":16.04},{"text":"I stand corrected on that.","start":2529.665,"stop":2532.838,"duration":3.17}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I can't find any in the record, any of these papers that underlay either those application.","start":2532.838,"stop":2537.823,"duration":4.98},{"text":"Are they in this record, do you know Mr. Rinehart?","start":2537.823,"stop":2539.629,"duration":1.81},{"text":"Are they not in (Voice Overlap) --","start":2539.629,"stop":2540.602,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"No they are not in this record.","start":2540.602,"stop":2542.388,"duration":1.79},{"text":"They are not --","start":2542.388,"stop":2543.035,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- filed with this Court, are they?","start":2543.035,"stop":2544.456,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"They have not.","start":2544.456,"stop":2545.2,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"None of these underlying papers with --","start":2545.2,"stop":2547.6,"duration":2.4}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Not to my knowledge.","start":2547.6,"stop":2548.883,"duration":1.28},{"text":"The printed record in this case which consists of petition for writ of certiorari in exhibits is the record in the case.","start":2548.883,"stop":2561.735,"duration":12.85}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is the original petition on the writ -- the contempt order was issued in the record before us.","start":2561.735,"stop":2567.564,"duration":5.83},{"text":"I did not find any --","start":2567.564,"stop":2569.295,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"It is included --","start":2569.295,"stop":2569.855,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- state's petition.","start":2569.855,"stop":2571.156,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"The state's petition is included in the record.","start":2571.156,"stop":2573.357,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is it?","start":2573.357,"stop":2580.035,"duration":6.68}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Record pages 1, 2 and 3.","start":2580.035,"stop":2592.286,"duration":12.25}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, that's the petition --","start":2592.286,"stop":2593.586,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's their petition.","start":2593.586,"stop":2596.375,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I stand corrected, what I should say is that this is a synopsis and rather of our petition.","start":2596.375,"stop":2604.312,"duration":7.94},{"text":"It is not the petition itself, I stand corrected.","start":2604.312,"stop":2607.593,"duration":3.28},{"text":"The petition itself that we filed in the initial proceedings is not in this record.","start":2607.593,"stop":2615.403,"duration":7.81}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Rinehart, do you suppose, I don't know if it's appropriate or not.","start":2615.403,"stop":2618.407,"duration":3},{"text":"You tell if me if you don't think so, if you don't believe it is.","start":2618.407,"stop":2621.701,"duration":3.29},{"text":"Could we have -- provided us the record and all of these applications to your Supreme Court, the petitions that were filed?","start":2621.701,"stop":2631.422,"duration":9.72}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I have -- do not have them with me here.I am certain that if as for -- they will all be supplied.","start":2631.422,"stop":2639.902,"duration":8.48},{"text":"All that was before the Supreme Court was set up that was asked for from the Supreme Court.","start":2639.902,"stop":2645.973,"duration":6.07},{"text":"Now in addition, there were -- was this initial petition for certiorari -- I'm not addressing myself now to our petition but this initial petition for certiorari which page -- appears at pages 16 and 17 of the record.","start":2645.973,"stop":2669.326,"duration":23.35},{"text":"I should again qualify that statement by saying that these are the grounds alleged in that and that all that was alleged in it was what I call an assignment of error.","start":2669.326,"stop":2677.076,"duration":7.75}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"As I understand -- as I understand, the only one we have here is a petition which was filed on the 20th of August.","start":2677.076,"stop":2682.184,"duration":5.11}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":2682.184,"stop":2682.652,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And apparently there was a petition filed somewhere on August the 13th which we do not have and as to which your court -- the Supreme Court said that the averments were insufficient.","start":2682.652,"stop":2694.352,"duration":11.7},{"text":"Then before that on July 31, there must have been some kind of paper filed in connection with the motion for stay and we don't have that paper either.","start":2694.352,"stop":2703.634,"duration":9.28}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":2703.634,"stop":2706.78,"duration":3.15},{"text":"We did -- we concurred in the record in this case.","start":2706.78,"stop":2709.786,"duration":3.01}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I notice that from the file in the clerk's office.","start":2709.786,"stop":2716.853,"duration":7.07}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Rinehart, your time is just about up.I wanted to confess yourself to the merits.","start":2716.853,"stop":2723.252,"duration":6.4}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I should be happy to, Your Honor.","start":2723.252,"stop":2724.747,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You still have a few moments before you can sit down.","start":2724.747,"stop":2727.988,"duration":3.24}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, there are really several questions of the merits involved here.","start":2727.988,"stop":2733.693,"duration":5.71},{"text":"There is first the merit -- the question of the state's power to take any such initial action and we based that on the plenary common law powers of the Attorney General of Alabama to vindicate and enforce the public policy of Alabama concerning the domestication of foreign corporations.","start":2733.693,"stop":2753.14,"duration":19.45},{"text":"I'm talking about that constitutional provision, Section 232 which is self-implementing.","start":2753.14,"stop":2758.784,"duration":5.64},{"text":"We think that an Attorney General has the inherent right and in fact --","start":2758.784,"stop":2762.181,"duration":3.4}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Where is that printed that constitutional provision?","start":2762.181,"stop":2764.975,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"It is not set out in the briefs, I have it here.","start":2764.975,"stop":2769.97,"duration":4.99},{"text":"I'm now reading from the Alabama Code of 1940 which also includes the Alabama Constitution, Article XII Section 232.","start":2769.97,"stop":2777.722,"duration":7.75}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What does it say?","start":2777.722,"stop":2779.503,"duration":1.78},{"text":"What is it?","start":2779.503,"stop":2780.242,"duration":0.74},{"text":"Would you mind reading --","start":2780.242,"stop":2780.983,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I -- Right now.","start":2780.983,"stop":2783.999,"duration":3.02},{"text":"“No foreign corporation shall do any business in this state without having at least one known place of business and an authorized agent or agents therein, and without filing that the Secretary of State has certified copy of its articles of incorporation or association.","start":2783.999,"stop":2805.943,"duration":21.94},{"text":"Such corporation maybe sued in any county where it does business by service of process upon an agent anywhere in the state.","start":2805.943,"stop":2816.312,"duration":10.37},{"text":"The legislature shall, by general law, provide for the payment to the State of Alabama of a franchise tax by such corporation, but such franchise tax shall be based on the actual amount of capital employed in this State.","start":2816.312,"stop":2831.634,"duration":15.32},{"text":"Strictly benevolent, educational or religious corporations shall not be required to pay such tax.”","start":2831.634,"stop":2839.567,"duration":7.93}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Your time has expired but you have may have five minutes more to summarize -- summarize the merits of the -- you stick to the merits.","start":2839.567,"stop":2845.432,"duration":5.86}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I certainly shall.","start":2845.432,"stop":2846.686,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2846.686,"stop":2849.758,"duration":3.07}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I was saying that we have the plenary common law powers that the Attorney General of Alabama is a constitutional officer who has the same powers which the Attorney General of Great Britain had at common law.","start":2849.758,"stop":2863.186,"duration":13.43},{"text":"We depend upon those cases, a long line of cases which say that a corporation doing intrastate business in a state or rather the Supreme Court decisions which say that a corporation maybe prevented doing intrastate business within a state if it hasn't first gone there and conform to the laws of that state.","start":2863.186,"stop":2885.773,"duration":22.59}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there any law of Alabama which tells a delinquent corporation cannot register -- cannot register?","start":2885.773,"stop":2891.687,"duration":5.91}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Absolutely not, no statutory law whatsoever.","start":2891.687,"stop":2894.776,"duration":3.09}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"In considering the merits, it means that (Inaudible).","start":2894.776,"stop":2899.555,"duration":4.78},{"text":"You would tell me what issue was left upon which an order could rest (Inaudible)","start":2899.555,"stop":2908.758,"duration":9.2}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Whether --","start":2908.758,"stop":2909.095,"duration":0.34}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- after you had, on your petition, you oust these people because they were delinquent after they had offered to file the Secretary's claims, a certificate, which if they have been permitted to file, he could not have (Inaudible).","start":2909.095,"stop":2927.415,"duration":18.32},{"text":"What issue was left on which orders could be issued in your brief after that?","start":2927.415,"stop":2934.075,"duration":6.66}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- think that the -- the authority to oust is -- is in the Courts of Alabama to punish -- perhaps punish is not -- is too strong a word, but to -- I believe it is a correct one for having -- for a long period of time ignored our laws and the question of whether in fact they were doing business and how long in the extent and nature of there -- were absolutely essential to the case.","start":2934.075,"stop":2959.491,"duration":25.42},{"text":"Now, we think that the power to oust for past misconduct included the power to maintain the status quo as between the parties, and that is what this order denying the right to register did.","start":2959.491,"stop":2973.189,"duration":13.7},{"text":"It's the traditional power of the court of equity.","start":2973.189,"stop":2976.488,"duration":3.3}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Had they ever done that?","start":2976.488,"stop":2978.554,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2978.554,"stop":2978.972,"duration":0.42},{"text":"We've never had an -- we've never had a case like this before.","start":2978.972,"stop":2982.623,"duration":3.65}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Never had a case where a corporation was delinquent?","start":2982.623,"stop":2986.779,"duration":4.16}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"We've had cases where -- where corporations -- oh, I won't say that.","start":2986.779,"stop":2991.205,"duration":4.43},{"text":"I don't know of anywhere corporations were delinquent in this manner.","start":2991.205,"stop":2996.885,"duration":5.68},{"text":"There are other constitutional questions -- I don't want to dodge that question, Your Honor.","start":2996.885,"stop":3000.462,"duration":3.58}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't want to consume all your time on this but I had been wondering if this -- is this -- if they had been permitted to file this registration certificate with the Secretary of State.","start":3000.462,"stop":3014.296,"duration":13.83},{"text":"He could not have refused it, couldn't he?","start":3014.296,"stop":3018.08,"duration":3.78}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"There's -- there is a dispute in our opinion which has never been written, I admit.","start":3018.08,"stop":3021.887,"duration":3.81},{"text":"Our opinion is that he could, first of all, he has the duty to refer it to the franchise tax people for determination of whether or not in fact this is a benevolent corporation within the meaning of the law of exemptions or a charitable and --","start":3021.887,"stop":3035.367,"duration":13.48}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"And suppose they offered to file these both, could he have refused it?","start":3035.367,"stop":3039.067,"duration":3.7}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, he doesn't -- he doesn't in fact accept the filing and it is not accepted until the franchise tax people make a determination as to whether or not there are franchise taxes due.","start":3039.067,"stop":3049.69,"duration":10.62},{"text":"That's my understanding of the procedure.","start":3049.69,"stop":3052.316,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Was there any basis for this action originally except that they were delinquent in registration?","start":3052.316,"stop":3060.597,"duration":8.28}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"That --","start":3060.597,"stop":3061.881,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"The pleadings are not here that's the reason I don't know.","start":3061.881,"stop":3064.172,"duration":2.29}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"The basis for the action is that they were delinquent -- the basis of the action is a long-term extensive delinquency which we think is in derogation of the rights of the people of Alabama not to have corporations come in, foreign corporations, and just ignore their statutes.","start":3064.172,"stop":3081.371,"duration":17.2}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What do you say about their membership?","start":3081.371,"stop":3084.469,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean why is that relevant?","start":3084.469,"stop":3087.245,"duration":2.78}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, there decision of (Inaudible).","start":3087.245,"stop":3097.834,"duration":10.59}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I disagree with that contention entirely.","start":3097.834,"stop":3101.275,"duration":3.44},{"text":"I don't believe a corporation has any right of privacy and that any case of this Court or -- has ever held any such thing.","start":3101.275,"stop":3110.011,"duration":8.74},{"text":"I can address myself to that.","start":3110.011,"stop":3111.405,"duration":1.39},{"text":"I think the recent cases such as Watkins and Sweezy are questions of assertions of individual rights, I see.","start":3111.405,"stop":3116.941,"duration":5.54}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But what -- before you sit down, your doubt is familiar with the joint facet of cases.","start":3116.941,"stop":3123.6,"duration":6.66}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":3123.6,"stop":3124.48,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"And therefore your doubt is familiar with the diversity of views expressed.","start":3124.48,"stop":3128.32,"duration":3.84}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I am.","start":3128.32,"stop":3129.437,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"So that one cannot say that there was anything but a single judgment.","start":3129.437,"stop":3133.23,"duration":3.79},{"text":"But you will recall, Mr. Justice Jackson, in which he sustain standing to sue on the part of the corporate entities, the non-individual bodies that would be forced in that case on the ground that if the individuals cannot assert their constitutional claim, members, in other words in an organization which is asked to make disclosure and the individuals who are members can't themselves come in to protect what they claim to be a constitutional right without frustrating, without nullifying the very right which they claim by making a disclosure.","start":3133.23,"stop":3179.803,"duration":46.57},{"text":"But then, the corporate body can assert those individual rights.","start":3179.803,"stop":3182.851,"duration":3.05},{"text":"In short, assuming that individuals in Alabama, inherently appropriate (Inaudible) and say you can't ask us whether we belong to the N.A.A.C.P, that's a territory that is protected, I'm making that assumption.","start":3182.851,"stop":3203.542,"duration":20.69}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand.","start":3203.542,"stop":3204.079,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Otherwise there's no point.","start":3204.079,"stop":3206.628,"duration":2.55},{"text":"We -- we can withhold -- we don't have to tell Alabama or New York or anybody else to what club we belong provided that it isn't a tradition to organization.","start":3206.628,"stop":3215.776,"duration":9.15},{"text":"I'm putting that to one.","start":3215.776,"stop":3218.879,"duration":3.1},{"text":"That's our constitutional right.","start":3218.879,"stop":3221.45,"duration":2.57},{"text":"But if we go -- have to go on to court and say, if what you were asking the organization to do make hindrance on my right and by that very proceeding, you nullify your rights.","start":3221.45,"stop":3234.264,"duration":12.81},{"text":"Then the corporate body having this undisclosable -- this list of undisclosable membership does have a standing to speak for the individual members.","start":3234.264,"stop":3246.583,"duration":12.32}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"My first answer of course is I don't agree with that portion of the opinion but I will also direct --","start":3246.583,"stop":3253.254,"duration":6.67}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It wasn't an opinion.","start":3253.254,"stop":3254.095,"duration":0.84},{"text":"It was an individual's opinion.","start":3254.095,"stop":3255.12,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Individual opinion, that's what I mean, Mr. Justice Jackson.","start":3255.12,"stop":3256.756,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"He maybe was quite candid in saying that he thought the corporation would not have standing to sue except in this (Inaudible) the individual right does come into action.","start":3256.756,"stop":3271.045,"duration":14.29}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":3271.045,"stop":3271.413,"duration":0.37},{"text":"I -- I would -- if I may address myself exactly to that question.","start":3271.413,"stop":3274.807,"duration":3.39},{"text":"First of all, Mr. Justice Jackson, preliminarily to holding -- making that statement held that a corporation had no right of privacy, that in fact if all the order of the Attorney General in that case had done was hold individual members up to contumely and unpopularity and all of the things which I might say are speculative in the instant case, through speculation, that if that were all, he would say that the corporation did have any standing but that would had happened and remind -- I want to remind you that it was entirely state action.","start":3274.807,"stop":3309.682,"duration":34.88},{"text":"Both the first and second pressures brought there was entirely state action.","start":3309.682,"stop":3314.961,"duration":5.28},{"text":"One was the ex parte action of the Attorney General in declaring the organization subversive which I -- insofar there is a majority opinion I would say the basis of it and then you get to the next step which was by virtue of that order, here, where a lot of innocent people who are going to lose jobs automatically state job -- and the jobs which they were going to lose automatically were government jobs so that was obviously government action.","start":3314.961,"stop":3345.91,"duration":30.95},{"text":"Now I -- perhaps I haven't exactly answered the content -- that is how I explained that decision.","start":3345.91,"stop":3351.345,"duration":5.43}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But I suggest and I suppose what is behind this claim of refusal to disclose the individual members of the N.A.A.C.P. and Alabama.","start":3351.345,"stop":3360.904,"duration":9.56},{"text":"I've taken that direct to pleading but I take it the thought is and the reason for this claim why the individuals don't step forward is because they are potentially in a damageable condition if they do make disclosure.","start":3360.904,"stop":3375.147,"duration":14.24},{"text":"That's how they were told.","start":3375.147,"stop":3376.313,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Damageable from whom is that important question.","start":3376.313,"stop":3379.605,"duration":3.29},{"text":"First of all, I would want to make a point which bears precisely on --","start":3379.605,"stop":3383.654,"duration":4.05}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Damageable by the State.","start":3383.654,"stop":3385.491,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, the State isn't going to bring any pressure to bear on these individuals.","start":3385.491,"stop":3389.072,"duration":3.58}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The pressure derived from the fact that the State compelled a disclosure if they may just as it's going to fascist case if one of these organizations and the Attorney General had to make closed.","start":3389.072,"stop":3402.11,"duration":13.04},{"text":"It would affect people.","start":3402.11,"stop":3404.163,"duration":2.05},{"text":"It doesn't make any difference whether it's an private employment or public employment so long as the governmental authority takes away something that it can't -- can't take away?","start":3404.163,"stop":3413.126,"duration":8.96}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't believe that there is anything in the law that says that the mere fact that a person may become unpopular as a result of a disclosure gives him a constitutional right to keep a secret.","start":3413.126,"stop":3427.425,"duration":14.3}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"That isn't the implication of my question.","start":3427.425,"stop":3429.55,"duration":2.13},{"text":"Is it inconceivable that an individual might bring in a -- bring a suit in Alabama and say if I make a disclosure that I'm a member of the N.A.A.C.P., I lose my business.","start":3429.55,"stop":3438.742,"duration":9.19},{"text":"Is that inconceivable hypothesis?","start":3438.742,"stop":3442.578,"duration":3.84}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I have a hard time feeling that that -- there would be probably an embarrassing word of justiciable issue there.","start":3442.578,"stop":3449.175,"duration":6.6}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What -- to lose business?","start":3449.175,"stop":3450.868,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Unless he can get -- bring it against an alleged extremely specific details in that.","start":3450.868,"stop":3457.482,"duration":6.61},{"text":"In other words, say that this person is without justification causing me to lose my business.","start":3457.482,"stop":3463.041,"duration":5.56}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well this person being -- the starting point is that the State of Alabama or any other -- the State of Massachusetts doesn't make a difference so far as I'm concerned, the state is asking me to make a disclosure which I am entitled to withhold and by making such disclosure, my business will be shut down.","start":3463.041,"stop":3485.43,"duration":22.39},{"text":"The Government isn't shutting down the business but it is taking action which results in the shutting down and that's not justiciable.","start":3485.43,"stop":3494.279,"duration":8.85}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Because the -- the thing which may -- which may and that's pure speculation in the allegations in here (Voice Overlap) --","start":3494.279,"stop":3499.422,"duration":5.14}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they can't -- they may not be able to make good on that.","start":3499.422,"stop":3501.795,"duration":2.37},{"text":"They may not be able to make good on that but if you -- supposed the joint fascist suit that old case turned on the fact that the Attorney General have filed what is practically a demurrer and said -- well suppose everything you say is so, that's the basis on which I have -- one has to meet these legal question.","start":3501.795,"stop":3519.267,"duration":17.47}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Sir?","start":3519.267,"stop":3520.391,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Assume it's so that John Smith and whatever it is in Alabama -- sometimes Alabama says, “I received a request from the Attorney General to tell him -- to tell me whether I'm a member of N.A.A.C.P. and I refused to do so.”","start":3520.391,"stop":3538.188,"duration":17.8},{"text":"And he says, “Well that's required by some decree of the Court and if I make this disclosure which I'm entitled to refuse to make, I will suffer and my business.","start":3538.188,"stop":3551.03,"duration":12.84},{"text":"Would that be demurrable?","start":3551.03,"stop":3553.571,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe it would and I will explain why.","start":3553.571,"stop":3555.93,"duration":2.36},{"text":"I believe neither the Sweezy cases and the Watkins case which seemed to pair on this right to not to have to testify about associations, our answer on this basis that in this case, we have relevancy to a judicial proceeding and we submit an extremely valid judicial proceeding and I might add in this particular --","start":3555.93,"stop":3579.554,"duration":23.62}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean mandamus?","start":3579.554,"stop":3581.098,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no, no, to the -- to the central issue in the case whether they're doing business in Alabama and whether they should be ousted.","start":3581.098,"stop":3586.996,"duration":5.9}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"But supposed you win on that, and that supposed you can oust the in the meantime, supposed you are entitled to oust them, it doesn't follow from that that individuals may have to make disclosure that they were members of the ousted corporation.","start":3586.996,"stop":3601.493,"duration":14.5}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I agree.","start":3601.493,"stop":3602.02,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"If that -- if they can allege and subsequently prove that in fact the human inevitable consequence is material monetary mundane punishment and their property interest.","start":3602.02,"stop":3617.299,"duration":15.28}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think a person has such immunity from testifying in a case that he is properly subpoenaed.","start":3617.299,"stop":3621.84,"duration":4.54}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's -- that was the demerit of whether such an exertion can be made.","start":3621.84,"stop":3627.042,"duration":5.2}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, it does and I -- I can't -- I failed to find any judicial authority for that particular --","start":3627.042,"stop":3634.86,"duration":7.82}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"What you're saying is that Alabama tomorrow can subpoena a lot of individuals in this litigation, supposed this proceeds because you're allowed to proceed at the ouster proceeding.","start":3634.86,"stop":3645.468,"duration":10.61},{"text":"What you're saying is that as a matter of substantive constitutional law, if Alabama's subpoena Smith Jones Robinson and asked him on a -- him or her on the stand, “Are you now or were you a member of N.A.A.C.P.?”","start":3645.468,"stop":3660.584,"duration":15.12},{"text":"They could not say, Your Honor, in every respect, I decline to answer because I'm protected by the Constitution.","start":3660.584,"stop":3666.693,"duration":6.11},{"text":"That's what you say is it?","start":3666.693,"stop":3668.372,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that we would have to show that our questions were relevant to the issues in the case.","start":3668.372,"stop":3671.165,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm assuming there, yes.","start":3671.165,"stop":3674.95,"duration":3.78}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't believe that he could.","start":3674.95,"stop":3676.377,"duration":1.43},{"text":"In fact, I -- deny that he could.","start":3676.377,"stop":3678.14,"duration":1.76}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"Very well.","start":3678.14,"stop":3679.117,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"I wish I could -- I do not detain anyone further in this matter.","start":3679.117,"stop":3687.126,"duration":8.01}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Carter.","start":3687.126,"stop":3691.015,"duration":3.89}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"If the Court please, Mr. Justice Brennan and Mr. Justice Black.","start":3691.015,"stop":3695.821,"duration":4.81},{"text":"I expressed some interest in some of the pleadings which are not here.","start":3695.821,"stop":3701.922,"duration":6.1},{"text":"As you know, this was an ancillary proceeding and this was the record which was certified and printed from the court -- the Supreme Court of Alabama.","start":3701.922,"stop":3710.526,"duration":8.6},{"text":"If the Court desires and with the Court's permission, I would -- could undertake to get the motions and all the other pleadings if that's -- if that is what is desired with respect to the motion to stay and the first petition for writ of certiorari, the bill of complaint filed by the state and our answer.","start":3710.526,"stop":3731.303,"duration":20.78},{"text":"That's -- if the Court decide for me to do that, I will certainly undertake to do that.","start":3731.303,"stop":3737.314,"duration":6.01}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You have them here?","start":3737.314,"stop":3738.967,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":3738.967,"stop":3739.683,"duration":0.72},{"text":"They -- we do not.","start":3739.683,"stop":3742.327,"duration":2.64},{"text":"They're in -- in my office in New York and I could have printed it.","start":3742.327,"stop":3747.006,"duration":4.68},{"text":"That's what the court wants me to do.","start":3747.006,"stop":3750.711,"duration":3.7}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't necessary have them printed but if you have a copy of them that can be delivered to our clerk, we do so and if you have any additional documents that you'd like to have filed on the clerk, you may do so also, Mr. Rinehart.","start":3750.711,"stop":3766.786,"duration":16.08}]},{"speakerName":"Edmon L. Rinehart","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) Your Honor.","start":3766.786,"stop":3769.333,"duration":2.55}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that the -- the ultimate question -- the preliminary question rather of jurisdiction, of course will be decided by this Court on a reading of the cases but on the questions that were asked to Mr. Rinehart, I would like to direct the Court's attention to page 15, an excerpt from Ex parte Dickens which we set out on page 15 of our petition for writ of certiorari which I think shows without question that on certiorari the Court does go using the validity and the merits of the order which is disobeyed.","start":3769.333,"stop":3813.468,"duration":44.13},{"text":"We think that --","start":3813.468,"stop":3813.691,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"It does go, Mr. Rinehart candidly admitted that in fact the Supreme Court goes ahead and talks about things which it says it merely talked about, it does so merely makes speeches because it restricts its decision to what it needs to restrict it to, namely, whether the jurisdictions may gain on the face of the document.","start":3813.691,"stop":3842.539,"duration":28.85}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":3842.539,"stop":3843.258,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words -- in other words if the State said we go on this ground -- on the state ground, you follow -- you've taken the wrong attorney, you followed the wrong procedure but we've got lose up here, we talk about things we didn't even talk about and so we make a speech.","start":3843.258,"stop":3862.504,"duration":19.25}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think Mr. Justice Frankfurter that a reading of the cases which you applied will sustain that position except here.","start":3862.504,"stop":3872.128,"duration":9.62},{"text":"On certiorari, the Supreme Court of Alabama talks about First Amendment freedoms -- freedom from privilege of self-incrimination and indicate that this excerpt says that they will go into the merits and if they don't, these opinions are not that we need go no further.","start":3872.128,"stop":3890.626,"duration":18.5},{"text":"These opinions are clearly on point but as I said, the Court will read the decisions that come to its own conclusions.","start":3890.626,"stop":3899.838,"duration":9.21}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask Mr. Carter, are you suggesting that Dickens, Wheeler, Blakey, Boscowitz, Sellers and Morris support your position, is that it?","start":3899.838,"stop":3908.898,"duration":9.06}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":3908.898,"stop":3909.365,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And those are the ones you rely on particularly?","start":3909.365,"stop":3911.256,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Those are the ones that we rely on.","start":3911.256,"stop":3912.538,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What about Armstrong?","start":3912.538,"stop":3914.584,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well the Armstrong -- the reason I say that the Armstrong case was the -- merely to show that at times the Supreme Court of Alabama has treated these various papers file as even though they would call something else that treated them as the proper paper.","start":3914.584,"stop":3930.796,"duration":16.21},{"text":"In other words, Armstrong could have come up or should have come up to Alabama instead on certiorari.","start":3930.796,"stop":3936.958,"duration":6.16},{"text":"It was to call the petition for writ of mandamus and the Supreme Court of Alabama said, “We will treat as a petition --","start":3936.958,"stop":3943.461,"duration":6.5}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it said the affirmance, as I read it, were sufficient so that it might be considered as a petition for certiorari.","start":3943.461,"stop":3949.021,"duration":5.56}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Because of the fact that in the Alabama pleadings, one asked on these pleadings for such other and further relief as the Court may deem appropriate.","start":3949.021,"stop":3959.4,"duration":10.38},{"text":"On the basis of that, the Supreme Court of Alabama said that we will treat this as a petition for writ of certiorari which crosses an entirely different question and we merely raised this to show that the procedure is not as strict on this issue as -- as the state attempts to maintain.","start":3959.4,"stop":3980.754,"duration":21.35}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"On what -- on what did you -- from what did you take your petition for certiorari in the Court -- the Supreme Court --","start":3980.754,"stop":3988.697,"duration":7.94}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"We took our petition for writ of certiorari to the Supreme Court from the interlocutory or the restraining order from the first and second adjudications of contempt.","start":3988.697,"stop":4001.86,"duration":13.16}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's the contempt?","start":4001.86,"stop":4002.662,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4002.662,"stop":4003.832,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"As the Supreme Court of Alabama unless at this case, made a specific repudiation on what it said in Ex parte Dickens?","start":4003.832,"stop":4014.494,"duration":10.66}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"No, sir.","start":4014.494,"stop":4015.957,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"In that case, they head up the question of certiorari as a proper remedy for -- to review contempt.","start":4015.957,"stop":4024.291,"duration":8.33},{"text":"The Court said, “We think that certiorari has a better remedy than mandamus, because the office of a mandamus is to require the lower court adjudge an act and not to correct error as the reverse -- on a reversed judicial action.","start":4024.291,"stop":4041.621,"duration":17.33},{"text":"And that's been referred to in litigation?","start":4041.621,"stop":4044.908,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"That has not been repudiated.","start":4044.908,"stop":4046.522,"duration":1.61},{"text":"That has been the laws, we understood it until the decision in this case.","start":4046.522,"stop":4051.31,"duration":4.79}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"So far as this case referred to in the, you say the Supreme Court?","start":4051.31,"stop":4055.474,"duration":4.16}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Ex parte Dickens was referred to in the decision of the Supreme Court.","start":4055.474,"stop":4059.11,"duration":3.64}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"In this case.","start":4059.11,"stop":4059.771,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"In this case.","start":4059.771,"stop":4061.042,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"What -- what was said about it?","start":4061.042,"stop":4064.296,"duration":3.25}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible) Beginning on page 24 of the last paragraph, the Court says -- of the record -- I'm sorry.","start":4064.296,"stop":4083.641,"duration":19.35}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Of the record.","start":4083.641,"stop":4083.806,"duration":0.16}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Of the record, yes.","start":4083.806,"stop":4088.595,"duration":4.79},{"text":"Well, we've set out the Court's opinion.","start":4088.595,"stop":4091.527,"duration":2.93},{"text":"The Court says, “On the petition for certiorari, the sole and only reviewable order or decree is that which adjudged the petitioner to be in contempt.Certiorari cannot be made a substitute for an appeal or other method of review.","start":4091.527,"stop":4104.558,"duration":13.03},{"text":"Certiorari lies to review an order of judgment of contempt for the reason that there is no other method of review citing Ex parte Dickens.","start":4104.558,"stop":4114.368,"duration":9.81}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"They also referred to and they distinguished it on the ground that one would show them on one criminal contempt?","start":4114.368,"stop":4122.721,"duration":8.35}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"They -- as I understand the decision here, they -- the distinction between civil and criminal contempt is not the reach of certiorari but the question of what fine the court below may impose.","start":4122.721,"stop":4137.846,"duration":15.13},{"text":"In criminal contempt on Alabama law, the Court is limited by statutes to the amount of fine that for an individual, they can across toward an individual order and across with five days and a fine of $50.","start":4137.846,"stop":4152.121,"duration":14.28},{"text":"On civil contempt, the court's power is unlimited to the -- to the kind of punishment it may impose and this was the distinction which apparently the -- which apparently to which the Court makes with respect to this case.","start":4152.121,"stop":4168.113,"duration":15.99},{"text":"As we read the decision on Ex parte Dickens as referred to throughout the opinion, the Court was really misquoting and misciting its own decisions because Ex parte Dickens specifically says that certiorari used to be limited by jurisdiction of the questions of jurisdiction but now it could reach the question of the merits.","start":4168.113,"stop":4200.101,"duration":31.99},{"text":"I assume my time is up but I just wanted --","start":4200.101,"stop":4202.047,"duration":1.95}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"You may -- you may have five minutes if you wish to -- to summarize your -- your argument Mr. --","start":4202.047,"stop":4207.311,"duration":5.26}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":4207.311,"stop":4209.797,"duration":2.49},{"text":"Well, our position here in our contentions that this is not appropriately a proceeding to require us out to register.","start":4209.797,"stop":4223.172,"duration":13.38},{"text":"I think that's clear from what was said today and it's clear from the papers and what has been -- what has happened in this case.","start":4223.172,"stop":4232.177,"duration":9.01},{"text":"If the Alabama wanted the corporation to register, we offered to register and we would have done so.","start":4232.177,"stop":4241.707,"duration":9.53},{"text":"Now, so this is really not what this case is all about.","start":4241.707,"stop":4246.651,"duration":4.94},{"text":"We think that Alabama, because of the ideas which we expose that Alabama has sought to use the far failure to register which they knew for a long number of years and which has been very obvious in Alabama for -- for many years, our failure to register as a -- as a device to suppress the organization and to get ousters from the State.","start":4246.651,"stop":4274.677,"duration":28.03}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I don't want to take your time but I understand why you're arguing this because unless I completely misunderstood Mr. Rinehart, the State isn't arguing here that we have to pass on Alabama's right of ouster.","start":4274.677,"stop":4287.96,"duration":13.28},{"text":"That isn't the issue at all.","start":4287.96,"stop":4290.756,"duration":2.8}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I understand the --","start":4290.756,"stop":4293.579,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"Felix Frankfurter","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the issue here is the validity of the contempt order as against certain constitutional claim, is that right?","start":4293.579,"stop":4301.245,"duration":7.67}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":4301.245,"stop":4303.394,"duration":2.15},{"text":"But our position is, if the Court please, that at the very outset, the Alabama court, the Court in this instance took illegal action because the only action that we are aware of that Alabama could exert against the corporation for failure to register was the action which is the statutory penalties which are set out on our brief at page 35.","start":4303.394,"stop":4328.956,"duration":25.56},{"text":"So, we are faced at the very outset, we're being put out of business without a hearing and then being ordered as a condition of -- of having a hearing on the merits.","start":4328.956,"stop":4339.829,"duration":10.87},{"text":"Of that -- at that point, we are then required to either submit to what we consider unconstitutional conditions or in effect stay ousted and have a final judgment entered against us in effect because we cannot prosecute this claim until the contempt proceedings had been finally adjudicated.","start":4339.829,"stop":4362.545,"duration":22.72},{"text":"As I indicated yesterday, our view is that the order requiring our members to -- requiring a production of the names of our members has no relevance to the question as to whether or not we are doing business in the state and particularly we believe this is so since we have taken that issue out of the case by ourselves indicating to the state that we are willing to comply with the law insofar as registration is concerned.","start":4362.545,"stop":4390.225,"duration":27.68}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you know Mr. Carter that the court's order of requiring such and that order stands until vacated by some procedure which Alabama (Inaudible)?","start":4390.225,"stop":4404.31,"duration":14.09}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":4404.31,"stop":4405.899,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Or whether the -- until it's at least raised in some way which the Alabama law specifies.","start":4405.899,"stop":4416.225,"duration":10.33}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you -- you're talking of the temporary restraining order?","start":4416.225,"stop":4418.058,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4418.058,"stop":4419.077,"duration":1.02},{"text":"I know -- first thing I know.","start":4419.077,"stop":4420.608,"duration":1.53},{"text":"Now, I'm talking about the order to produce.","start":4420.608,"stop":4423.101,"duration":2.49}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":4423.101,"stop":4424.342,"duration":1.24},{"text":"Yes, sir (Voice Overlap) --","start":4424.342,"stop":4425.263,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"And this is the same thing too on the temporary restraining order.","start":4425.263,"stop":4429.132,"duration":3.87},{"text":"There, it was -- the Court has jurisdiction and power to handle it, the trial court whether it's right or wrong.","start":4429.132,"stop":4438.318,"duration":9.19},{"text":"Now, until a motion to dissolve, it has been denied (Inaudible) that Court, no way to go -- any place else and -- isn't that right?And therefore you haven't -- can't have a review of that temporary injunction until you have had an order of willing the motion to dissolve.","start":4438.318,"stop":4465.638,"duration":27.32}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we think that that order was put in issue, necessarily put in issue by the opinion of the Supreme Court of Alabama which indicated that the Court below had jurisdiction that when it went to the question that we contend that it had no jurisdiction to oust this from the state on the basis of this pleading and that therefore the temporary restraining order is that issue because we raised it in the Supreme Court of Alabama.","start":4465.638,"stop":4495.329,"duration":29.69},{"text":"In other words, we think that not only is that Alabama wrong in ordering us to produce the names of our members but we think that at the outset, the state court was wrong in dissolving in fact, barring us from the State without a hearing because our contention is that there is no authority under the Alabama law and on the basis of this record for this to be done.","start":4495.329,"stop":4522.366,"duration":27.04}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"But the thing that you say barred you from Alabama was the temporary injunction.","start":4522.366,"stop":4527.371,"duration":5.01}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir.","start":4527.371,"stop":4528.201,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Can -- is that before us, can there be a review of the evidence and to point out until a motion to dissolve it has been presented and denied.","start":4528.201,"stop":4539.827,"duration":11.63}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, our theory, if the Court please, our theory is that it is before --- properly before the Court because Alabama acted arbitrarily in the first instance.","start":4539.827,"stop":4550.927,"duration":11.1}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"In issuing the order?","start":4550.927,"stop":4552.053,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"And that -- in issuing the temporary restraining order on the basis of this record that there was no jurisdiction.","start":4552.053,"stop":4557.419,"duration":5.37}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"No jurisdiction in the Court at all?","start":4557.419,"stop":4559.669,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, our contention is that there is no jurisdiction in Alabama Court to do what the restrainer under the basis -- on the basis of this record as a bond corporation or our failure to register.","start":4559.669,"stop":4570.497,"duration":10.83},{"text":"This is our contention and that we -- and that when the Court -- the Supreme Court of Alabama sustained jurisdiction that it necessarily approve the jurisdiction of the Court in this respect and that is before the Court here.","start":4570.497,"stop":4584.572,"duration":14.07}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think that it naturally follows if the court had no jurisdiction (Inaudible) then everything it did was of nullity.","start":4584.572,"stop":4591.815,"duration":7.24}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, our view is -- that is our view of course.","start":4591.815,"stop":4594.772,"duration":2.96},{"text":"Our view is that they have no right.","start":4594.772,"stop":4596.823,"duration":2.05},{"text":"That the only thing that the --","start":4596.823,"stop":4597.763,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Charles E. Whittaker","textObjs":[{"text":"Am I right, no jurisdiction?","start":4597.763,"stop":4599.065,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Robert L. Carter","textObjs":[{"text":"No jurisdiction, that the only power that the Alabama has upon the basis of our failure to register was to, one, require us to register or issues the statutory penalty set out in page 35 of our brief.","start":4599.065,"stop":4616.037,"duration":16.97}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Jan  15 - 16, 1958","petitioner":"National Association for the Advancement of Colored People","respondent":"Patterson","docket":"91","citation":"357 US 449 (1958)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/357/449","lowerCourt":"","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Jun 30, 1958"}